<li>Reeder , T. , and Schleif , R. ( 1993 ) AraC protein can activate transcription from only one position and when pointed in only one direction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>( B ) Test promoter RR Test promoter Gene product Protein function EvgA NarL NarP RcsB UhpA UvrY ydeO nirB nirB wza uhpT csrB AraC family transcription factor Nitrite reductase enzyme Regulation of acid resistance genes Reduction of nitrite to ammonia Reduction of nitrite to ammonia Capsular polysaccharide translocation Hexose-6-phosphate : phosphate antiporter Regulatory sRNA for carbon storage Nitrite reductase enzyme Outer membrane lipoprotein Major facilitator superfamily ( MFS ) transporter Small regulatory RNA ( sRNA ) Cross talk in vivo in promoter recognition between six NarL-family RRs The stage 3 cross talk in vivo was examined for a total of 30 combinations between six RRs and ﬁve representative promoters [ note that NarL and NarP recognize the same nirB promoter ] under the induction condition characteristic to each RR or in the presence and absence of over-expressed RRs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26010043" target="_blank">26010043</a>]<br></li>
<li>As far as we are aware , this is the first report of a direct interaction between CRP and an AraC family member ( although there may be a parallel with the interaction between CRP and CaiF reported by Buchet et al. , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>MarA is an AraC family global regulator ( Rhee et al. , 1998 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ) , which transcriptionally activates at least 21 promoters , the marA regulon ( Barbosa and Levy , 2000 ; Pomposiello et al. , 2001 ; Martin and Rosner , 2002 ; 2003 ) , by binding to a site ( marbox ) overlapping or upstream of the -35 signal ( Martin et al. , 1996 ; 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15225313" target="_blank">15225313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Introduction Most members of the AraC family of bacterial gene regulatory proteins are transcription activators that bind to speciﬁc 18 -- 20 bp sequences at target promoters : in many cases , activity is regulated by the binding of a small ligand ( reviewed by Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ; Egan , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Loop formation in viro and in vin ' o has been demonstrated in natural and artificial situations for a number of prokaryotic regulatory pro-reins including the Lacl , GalR , AraC , DeoR , ~ cI and P22 repressors ( reviewed in [ 49 ] ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7748925" target="_blank">7748925</a>]<br></li>
<li>The spacing hetwecn the ( ` Itt ' sit ' e and Ural was varied hv inserting t , hta following l ) KA seyarnces between positions -80 and - XI of / frflcHA II : 47 Minicircles plus AraC unlabeled aral DNA ( x ) minutes I araO2 Wild-type am02 mutant ¬ + - A + + -- O-5 5 29 AraC - - e + + HindIll - + + + + afall afab ¬ Diss .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848302" target="_blank">1848302</a>]<br></li>
<li>Well-studied examples are found among members of the AraC , LysR , and LuxR families , as well as in the OmpR and NarL families of phosphorylation-dependent response-regulator proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10913075" target="_blank">10913075</a>]<br></li>
<li>Examples of proteins that regulate carbon metabolism ( and the carbon source and species they are found in ) are AraC ( L-arabinose , Escherichia coli ) , RhaS and RhaR ( L-rhamnose , E. coli ) , XylS ( benzoates , Pseudomonas putida ) , and MelR ( melibiose , E. coli ) ( 2 , 14 , 33 , 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>No extensive similarity was found with the regulatory proteins AraC , RhaC , MelR , ArgR , BioR or LysR from E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1851954" target="_blank">1851954</a>]<br></li>
<li>This inhibitory function of the NTD is not found in MelR and RhaS/RhaR ( 18 , 56 , 58 ) but is found in AraC and XylS ( 15 , 41 , 59 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given that AraC 's is the only well-characterized allosteric-effector mechanism among AraC / XylS family proteins , we considered other mechanisms that could explain the allosteric effect of L-rhamnose on the activity of RhaS and RhaR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>This group includes AraC , RhaS , RhaR , and MelR from E. coli and XylS from Pseudomonas putida , which are among the most well characterized of the AraC/XylS family proteins ( 4 , 5 , 8 , 12 , 13 , 16 , 19 , 29 , 30 , 38 , 39 , 53 -- 55 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>Synergistic activation of a transcriptional-regulator together with CRP has been shown at several loci including the ara locus by AraC and CRP , malE by MalT and CRP , rha by RhaS / RhaR and CRP and asc by two CRP dimers , among others ( 37,44 -- 47 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24335284" target="_blank">24335284</a>]<br></li>
<li>Residue K593 of 70 has been found to be important for several transcription activators , including AraC , UhpA , cI , FNR , Ada , RhaR ( this study ) , and RhaS ( 4 , 24 , 27 , 35 , 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>]<br></li>
<li>Their more variable N-terminal regions may be primarily responsible for recognizing their respective inducers ; it is this portion of AraC and XylS in which mutations occur that alter the affinity or specificity for effectors ( 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1708380" target="_blank">1708380</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the signi ® cant stimulation of transcription from the cai and ® x promoters resulting from overproduction of CaiF in the absence of effector ( Table 1 ) indicates that , at suf ® ciently high concentration , some of the CaiF molecules become active in transcription , as described previously for XylS , an activator of the AraC family ( MarqueÂs and Ramos , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10564497" target="_blank">10564497</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , unlike AraC , deletion of N-terminal residues of RhaS and RhaR did not result in effector-independent phenotypes ( Table 1 ) , suggesting that the mechanism of their effector responses differ from that of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with the arm inhibiting activity in the absence of effector , N-terminal deletions of seven to 20 residues ( within the arm ) led to increased basal activation by AraC ( were constitutive ) ( Saviola et al. , 1998 ; Soisson et al. , 1997b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike AraC , Nterminal truncations suggested that RhaS and RhaR do n't use an N-terminal arm to inhibit activity in the absence of effector .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>If residues at the very N-terminus of RhaS or RhaR performed functions similar to the AraC Nterminal arm , then one or more N-terminal truncations would be predicted to result in activation of transcription in the absence of L-rhamnose to higher basal levels than wild-type RhaS or RhaR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>0022 ± 2836/98/180529 ± 10 $ 25.00 / 0/mb981713 # 1998 Academic Press Limite Results and Discussion Measurement of relative affinities of AraC for I1 , O2 , I2 and non-specific DNA To overcome the problems inherent in measuring absolute binding af ® nities , we accurately measured the relative af ® nities for AraC binding to various sites and formulated a quantitative description that utilized these relative af ® nities .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Let : KI1 be the af ® nity of AraC for the I1 half-site relative to its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA in the absence of arabinose , KI1arab be the af ® nity of AraC for the I1 half-site relative to its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA in the presence of arabinose , KO2 be the af ® nity of AraC for the O2 half-site relative to its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA in the absence of arabinose , KO2arab be the af ® nity of AraC for the O2 half-site relative to its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA in the presence of arabinose KI2 be the af ® nity of AraC for the I2 half-site relative to its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA in the absence of arabinose , KI2arab be the af ® nity of AraC for the I2 half-site relative to its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA in the presence of arabinose , Kns be the af ® nity of AraC for the ns , nonspeci ® c , half-site relative its af ® nity for non-speci ® c DNA , which equals 1 by de ® nition in the presence or absence of arabinose , N be the number of non-speci ® c half-sites to which AraC can loop to from I1 , P D KI1 KO2 T Lÿa0 P D KI1 KI2 T Cÿa0 and : DI1I2 I1I2 DI1O2 DI1ÿns D D P KI1 KI2 T Cÿa 1 P KI1 KI2 T Cÿa P KI1 KO2 T Lÿa N P K K T Lÿ I1 ns a In the presence of arabinose , the fraction in this I1I2 state is : aDI112 I112 aDI102 aDI1ÿns aD aD KI2arab KI1arab T C a P P T L a N a 1 KO2arab KI1arab C T P KI1arab KI2arab T L P KI1arab K ns a T , be the conversion from the half-site relative af ® nities to actual af ® nity of AraC for two adjacent half-sites ( thus the binding af ® nity for AraC to I1-I2 in the absence of arabinose equals KI1 KI2 T ) , Lÿa be a factor to include any overall preference for or against forming a loop in the absence of arabinose ( this factor includes the intrinsic pre-ference of AraC to loop and the possible consequences of interactions with RNA polymerase and CAP ; thus , the overall af ® nity for looping between I1 and O2 in the absence of arabinose is KI1 KO2 T Lÿa ) , L a be like Lÿa but in the presence of arabinose , Cÿa be whatever additional propensity or cost is involved in AraC binding to two adjacent half-sites minus arabinose ( from the de ® nition of T , Cÿa 1 ) , C a be like Cÿa but in the presence of arabinose , P be the effective concentration of free AraC protein per cell ( one molecule free per cell would be 10ÿ9 M ) , D be the concentration of ara regulatory region DNA free of bound AraC , Dxy be the concentration of ara regulatory region DNA with AraC bound at the half-sites x and y and , aDxy be like Dxy but in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>The four relevant states for which occupancies were calculated : no AraC bound ; AraC bound cis to half-sites I1 and I2 ; AraC bound to half-sites I1 and O2 and forming a DNA loop ; and AraC bound to half-site I1 and non-speci ® c , ns , DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Preliminary calculations showed that the most highly occupied states would be the following : free DNA , DNA with AraC bound at I1 and O2 , denoted I1O2 , DNA with AraC bound at I1 and I2 , denoted by I1I2 and DNA with AraC bound at I1 and at some non-speci ® c DNA position , denoted I1ns ( Figure 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>This was revealed by direct in vivo footprinting measurements in which the I2 half-site at pBAD was converted to the O2 sequence , and thus AraC had the opportunity to loop between I1 and either the distal O2 half-site or bind I1 and the adjacent half-site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consequently , we should be able to derive a quantitative description that predicts , under a wide variety of conditions , the fraction of operon copies in which AraC loops between I1 and O2 to repress pBAD and the fraction in which AraC binds to I1-I2 to induce pBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>We hypothesized that despite the extensive prior work on the AraC regulon , there are likely to be previously undescribed AraC-regulated genes and novel modes of regulation by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We identiﬁed seven putative target loci for AraC : upstream of araB-araC , araE , araF , araJ , ytfQ , ydeN , and within dcp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Speciﬁcally , we identiﬁed three novel binding targets of AraC ( upstream of ytfQ and ydeN and within dcp ) and ﬁve novel AraC-regulated genes ( ytfQ , ydeN , ydeM , ygeA , and polB ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In particular , we demonstrated here that the overexpression of gadX ( formerly called yhiX ) , which encodes a putative AraC family regulator ( Table 1 ) , in a wild-type strain increased the expression of H-NS-regulated genes involved in the response to low pH. Moreover , this strain showed a similar level of survival to the hns mutant at low pH in the presence of glutamate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11298273" target="_blank">11298273</a>]<br></li>
<li>That is , the AraCDimer-LexADNA chimera should act in a trans-dominant negative way to inactivate wild-type AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>This mutation renders the promoter unresponsive in vivo to stimulation by araC , and , in an AraC - cell , this mutant promoter is constitutive , possessing 26 % the level of wild-type , fully induced activity ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>This variant of the wild-type pBAD promoter possesses a normal basal level and can be activated by CAP to a high level even when AraC is not induced by arabinose ( reference 32 and data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
