<li>The concept of DNA looping was reinforced by the strict phasing requirement of the AraC binding sites for repression of the araBAD operon ( Dunn et al. , 1984 ; Lee & Schleif , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848637" target="_blank">1848637</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC protein stimulates expression of the araBAD operon and represses its own synthesis by binding at two different sites ( Lee et al. , 1981 ) , while the cI protein represses cro expression and simultaneously activates its own synthesis by binding at a single site , OR1 ( Ptashne et al. , 1976 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=6350602" target="_blank">6350602</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC protein is necessary for both positive and negative regulation of the araC-BAD operon , and alternate loops between AraC binding sites have been demonstrated under repressed and activated conditions ( Hamilt , on & Lee , 1988 ; Huo et al. , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848637" target="_blank">1848637</a>]<br></li>
<li>The promoter is regulated both positively and negativel , y by AraC ( Sheppard & Englesberg , 1967 ; Greenblatt & Schleif , 1971 ; Schleif & Lis , 1975 ; Dunn et al. , 1984 ) , a protein that binds to three operator sites upstream from pBAD ( see Fig. 1 ) ( Ogden et al. .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848302" target="_blank">1848302</a>]<br></li>
<li>The SoxS protein is related to the AraC family of transcriptional-activators , and it binds and activates all of the regulon promoters ( Amábile - Cuevas and Demple , 1991 ; Wu and Weiss , 1991 ; Li and Demple , 1994 ; Jair et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9019397" target="_blank">9019397</a>]<br></li>
