<li>Results ( a ) The ara0 , site is normally unoccupied in vi-vo One reason for the absence of repression of pBAD attributable to ara0 , could be that , despite the high affinity of AraC protein for this site , AraC protein binding to ara0 , may not occur in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possible explanation for the absence of AraC binding at ara0 , could be occlusion of the site due to DNA looping mediated by AraC protein bound at the flanking aral and ara02 sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overall , these results and previous published results suggest that even though AraC protein bound to each of the three binding sites in the araCBAD regulatory region has the potential to interact AraC protein at another site , poor occupancy of ara0 , in the absence of arabinose prevents this site from playing a significant role in DKA looping or repression of pBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro , repression of pBAD dependent on ara0 , could be shown when high concentrations of AraC protein were added to the reaction mixtures well before RNA polymerase so that AraC protein could occupy the ara0 , before RNA polymerase bound to the overlapping pc promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Discussion The ara0 , site contributes to repression of the ara pBAD promoter by means of DiSA looping between ara0 , and aral that is mediated by AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>The periodicity of pBAD repression with the ara0 , orientation suggests that the interaction of AraC protein bound to this site with AraC bound to aral is via DNA looping .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the experiments described in t ' his paper indicate that ' repression mediated by AraC protein binding to the ara0 , site can be observed when the in vivo concentration of AraC protein is raised well above normal physiological values ; they do not show that it is only a dimer of the prot , ein that is involved .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the experiments reported here we show first that AraC protein does not normally occupy the ara0 , site , but that increasing its level in the cell leads to occupancy of the site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>( d ) In vitro repression of p , , , deriving from ara0 1 Here we show that repression attributable to looping from araOl to ara1 can be observed in vitro by arranging that the ara0 , site is occupied by AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vivo a loo-fold overproduction of AraC protein and elimination of the ara0 , site gives repression of PBAD deriving from looping from ara0 , .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here we show , using both in vivo and in vitro experiments , that the ara0 , site is not normally occupied by AraC protein under repressing conditions , but that if AraC protein is overproduced and the ara0 , site is absent , ara0 , is then occupied and repression of pBAD can be observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>When the ara0 , site has been deleted and elevated levels of AraC protein are present , the ara0 , site can mediate repression in Go .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>When conditions in viva or in vitro are used such that ara0 , can be occupied by AraC protein , this site will contribute to repression of peAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since an increase in affinity of AraC is sufficient to give occupancy of araO , , we might expect also that increasing the intracellular concentration of Ara protein would lead to occupancy of ara0 , .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>While it is quite possible that AraC proteins interact through the â-barrel interface at higher protein concentrations , the strength of these interactions would be too weak to be relevant in the cell , where the concentration of the AraC protein has been estimated to be 1 × 10-8 M ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the original study , the sequenceto which AraCprotein binds appeared to have a hyphenated , % fold rotational symmetry , but the proposed symmetry is not supported by the data with mutant AraC protein ( 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since AraC binds araI and araFG2 with equal stoichiometry , we conclude that a dimer binds the araFG sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data suggest strongly that AraC protein is oriented on one side of the DNA double helix and binds to the DNA throughinteractions with specific bases in four adjacent major groove regions.Compared with the AraC contacts to the araBAD araI site , the FG1 and FG2 sites share highly conserved guanine contacts along three turns of the helix ( 2 3of Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The relative amount of AraC bound to the araFGl and araI sites was measured to see if AraC protein binds the araFG site with one or more additional AraC subunits .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The loop is formed when AraC protein binds to the upstream araO2 and the downstream araI half-sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>At both promoters AraC protein binds adjacent to RNA polymerase and CRP binds further upstream next to AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>RelativeStoichiometryof Binding to araFG and aral Sites-A dimer of AraC protein binds to the araI site in vitro ( 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC protein is primarily a dimer in solution , and it binds the araIBAD site as a dimer ( 28 , 43 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Assay of AraC protein binding to ara0 , is possible by in vivo footprinting with dimethylsulfate ( Martin et al. ; 1986 ) because AraC protein binding to the aral , ara0 , and ara0 , sites strongly increases the methyl-ation rate of one or two guanine nucleotides in the sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , the affinity of AraC protein for ara0 , seems more than adequate for binding , as its affi-nity in vitro for araO1 is more than 40-fold greater than its affinity for ara0 , and is equal to its aflinity for aral ( Hendrickson & Schleif , 1984 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since elevation of the intracellular level of AraC protein gave binding of the protein to araO , , it seems possible that looping could then occur between ara0 , and aral and that under these conditions repression might occur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although CAP activation requires the presence of AraC protein , sensitive in vitro studies did not detect any cooperative binding between CAP and AraC ( 16 , 37a ) , and in a minicircle assay , CAP actually slightly destabilized AraC binding ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>This absence and the potential for binding two dimers of the AraC protein to p imply that FGH AraC protein plays a signiﬁcant role in the activation of this promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7768852" target="_blank">7768852</a>]<br></li>
<li>Wickstrum , J.R. , Skredenske , J.M. , Kolin , A. , Jin , D.J. , Fang , J. and Egan , S.M. ( 2007 ) Transcription activation by the DNA-binding domain of the AraC family protein RhaS in the absence of its effector-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21398637" target="_blank">21398637</a>]<br></li>
<li>by araO2 The model is based on two key facts : ( i ) the DNA sites that bind AraC have very different affinities for the protein ( 15 , 16 ) and ( it ) the binding of ligand induces a conformational change in AraC that alters the sites of cooperative binding on the DNA ( ref .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our model extends the original proposal by Englesberg ( 5 ) that the AraC protein is biologically active in both its ligandbound and ligand-free states by binding specifically to different regions of the DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>Notwithstanding the results in this paper showing that the N-terminal half of AraC can participate in specific dimer formation , results do not eliminate the possibility that in our vivo the DNA-binding domains themselves of both AraC and LexA are unstable and are stabilized , but not dimerized , by additional protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>These authors suggest that as AraC binds to DNA , a large number of ions are displaced from the DNA but the majority of them rebind to the protein , thereby reducing the salt dependency on the binding constant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2405166" target="_blank">2405166</a>]<br></li>
<li>If AraC binds to DNA , two guanines in the AraC binding site become hypersensitive to DMS attack , and the extent of attack correlates well with the occupancy of the site by AraC protein ( 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
