<li>Therefore , it seemed likely that pE would not be induced until the AraC protein could ﬁnd its previously unoccupied binding site and that induction at pE would take signiﬁcantly longer than it takes for the AraC protein at pBAD to change conformations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7768852" target="_blank">7768852</a>]<br></li>
<li>We aral2 in propose that binding to araI2 results from an association between neighboring AraC protein molecules made possible by the ligand-induced conformational change .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two additional binding sites , araO2 and araI2 , are incapable of binding AraC protein when present alone , but each binds AraC cooperatively with araIl .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
