<li>AraC protection was from - 5 5 to - 1 0 0 and from - 1 3 6 to -173 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>This results in the formation of a repression loop and the repression of the araC promoter by AraC ( reviewed by Schleif , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that the degree of repression is proportional to the activity of the AraC mutant , with the highest degree of repression observed in the strong Leu9Pro mutant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-independent repression of ytfQ transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-dependent repression of ydeNM transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>of araC How AraC occupancy generates repression remains to be elucidated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on these results , we conclude that repression is AraC dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>If repression is due to AraC , then no repression will occur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>From our study , we can conclude that , though the ligandfree forms of both E. coli AraC and MelR proteins strongly repress expression from their own promoters , different mechanisms are used for ligand-dependent switching to a state that can activate transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This ﬁnding is similar to previous ﬁndings with the AraC and MelR proteins in which the activator binds to its upstream half-site much more tightly than its downstream half-site ( 8 , 9 , 18 , 31 ) and in the absence of ligand forms a DNA loop that represses transcription ( 30 , 41 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is possible that AraC regulates transcription from the site within sseD under conditions that derepress SPI2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that AraC bound at this site interacts with additional regulatory proteins , perhaps another monomer of AraC , bound closer to the transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of L-rhamnose , the AraC family activator RhaS ( reviewed in reference 12 ) binds to a site that spans from position 232 to position 281 relative to the rhaBAD transcription start site ( 9 , 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10852886" target="_blank">10852886</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the shorter fragment , from 371 to 1 , showed no repression by AraC , suggesting association of AraC with the sequence around the transcription start site ( Fig .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>When only one activator was added , low levels of PF ~ H transcription were obtained in the presence of CRP but not AraC protein , while previous studies have shown that transcription of Psst ) proceeds with AraC protein and not with CRP alone -LCB- Hahn et al. , 1986 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC and CRP were both required for maximal transcription in vitro , although a low level of transcription was detected with CRP alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>Maximal transcription was still dependent on AraC and CRP ; low levels of transcription , similar to those obtained with the wild type , were obtained for WH592 and WH603 with CRP alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>This domain alone could activate transcription of araBAD up to 15 % as well as full-length AraC when alone or to the same level as fulllength AraC when fused to an unrelated dimerization domain ( 7 , 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of these families have the opposite modes of action : RbsR is a classical repressor whose true inducer is D-ribose , whereas AraC and XylR are primarily activators of transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11750821" target="_blank">11750821</a>]<br></li>
<li>This , in turn , would affect induction by AraC and indirectly inﬂuence the transcription activity of ara pBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activated SoxR enhances the production of SoxS , a simple transcriptional-activator of the AraC family , which in turn , increases the transcription of the other genes of the regulon ( 4 , 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9030573" target="_blank">9030573</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose converts AraC from a repressor to an activator , and transcription of the three operons is rapidly and strongly induced ( 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10094697" target="_blank">10094697</a>]<br></li>
<li>S3 in the supplemental material ) , suggesting that AraC directly represses transcription of ytfQ , albeit weakly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>From this position , AraC activates transcription with the aid of the CAP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Read-through of inefﬁcient transcription terminators contributes to the E. coli AraC regulon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>CRP activation at some promoters , such as melAB and araBAD , is dependent on the presence of an additional regulator ( MelR and AraC , respectively ) ( 33,25 ) that is only induced by a speciﬁc substrate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15520470" target="_blank">15520470</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC , CRP I I I araBAD AraC AraC AraC I I AraC , CRP araC J ¬ I +100 I AraC AraC , CRP araE I l rI - t - Ag I I 3 ~ ~ ~ AA ~ rgR I argCBH ArgR I I !	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1943993" target="_blank">1943993</a>]<br></li>
<li>AB LE T Op Pr Reg Act Ada ada 0 0 0 1,2 126 AraC araBAD 1 1 0 1,2 59 , 70 AraC araC 1 1 0 1,2 48 AraC araE 0 1 0 2 145 CRP cat 0 0 0 2 72 CRP ccd 0 1 p 2,4 165 CRP colElpl 1 1 P ( ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1943993" target="_blank">1943993</a>]<br></li>
<li>Occupation of I2 results in transcription activation , presumably because AraC bound at I2 is able to interact directly with the RNA polymerase s subunit bound to the 235 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In light of the strict spacing and orientation requirements for AraC activation , interactions between AraC and RNA polymerase are likely to be speciﬁc and inﬂexible .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The lack of defect from 70 K593A , R599A , or R608A at the ( rhaS-lacZ ) 216 promoter is similar to previous ﬁndings with RhaS and AraC that substitutions at 70 some residues were defective only in the absence of CRP activation ( 4 , 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>]<br></li>
<li>The more recent ﬁnding that other s70 substitutions at positions near R596 , especially K593A , signiﬁcantly reduce activation by AraC in the absence of CRP supports the hypothesis that wild-type AraC and s70 make an interaction that contributes to transcription activation ( 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since transcription activation by AraC or FNR requires sCTD only in the absence of their respective coactivators , CAP or NarL ( 25 ) , we tested the effect of some alanine substitutions in sCTD on uhpT-lacZ expression in the Dcrp strain TM37 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10572130" target="_blank">10572130</a>]<br></li>
<li>Further , if these s70 residues are important for activation by RhaS in the absence of CRP , it is possible that other AraC / XylS family proteins that activate transcription without the aid of a second activator , such as CRP , may also require these residues .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>The lack of sequence dependence for the CRP site in the ara region may also be because the araBAD operon , unlike the gal and lac operons , depends not just on CRP activation but also on activation by a specific activator , AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activation of these in transcription at promoters requires , addition to CAP , the activating proteins AraC and MalT , respectively ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1569008" target="_blank">1569008</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro activation of the transcription of araBAD operon by AraC activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>The most intensely examined operon is araBAD , where AraC is required for repression and activation of BAD transcription ( reviewed by Schleif , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this case , the upstream CRP is needed for transcription activation in conjunction with AraC , but the role of CRP bound at downstream of the promoter remains unsolved .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24814025" target="_blank">24814025</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the cya mutant strain , CRP would not be bound to its site , and AraC would be the only activator of araBAD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>Studies of araE transcription in vitro confirm the results in vivo and show that promoter activity is directly stimulated by AraC and CRP ( Stoner & Schleif , 1983 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>The predominance of mutations affecting CRP is consistent with the central role of CRP in activation of the promoter ; CRP alone can stimulate the promoter both in vivo and in vitro , whereas AraC alone has no effect ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>This confirms that CRP is a primary activator of the promoter and that AraC alone is not capable of activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC and XylS , the namesakes of the family , are examples of two-domain family members in which the nonfamily domain functions in both effector binding and dimerization ( 7 , 19 , 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Table 1 , members of the AraC / XylS family regulate very diverse genes and functions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC family includes over 800 members , most of which are thought to be transcriptional-activators that function to regulate genes related to carbon metabolism , stress responses , or pathogenesis ( 9 -- 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>]<br></li>
<li>The location of Fis site I at nt 41 is analo-D 2 gous to the positions of other activators , such as the l repressor , MalT , AraC , and CRP ( in some cases ) , in which direct contact with s70 has been implicated ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7545153" target="_blank">7545153</a>]<br></li>
<li>The aim of this study was to test the dimer-switch model by characterizing in solution the intermolecular self-associa-tion of AraC mediated by the coiled-coil and â-barrel interfaces .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The importance of aligned residues AraC R251 and RhaR T279 in their respective mechanisms , however , suggests that the AraC and RhaR mechanisms may share the common principle of preventing contacts with σ70 in the absence of effector .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of bound ligand opens a second , â-barrel interaction interface that also mediates interactions between unliganded AraC dimers in the crystal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The three best-characterized proteins in this subgroup of the family are AraC , RhaR , and XylS ( 84 , 224 , 244 ; see below for further details ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequence accession numbers are : FeaR , EMBUGenBank X99402 ; XylS , SWISS-PROT P07859 ; RhaR , SWISS-PROT P09378 ; RhaS , SWISS-PROT P09377 ; AraC , SWISS-PROT P03021 ; MelR , SWISS-PROT P10411 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9043126" target="_blank">9043126</a>]<br></li>
<li>The overall fold of the NH2-terminal domain of AraC and the manner in which it binds ligand has not , to our knowledge , been previously observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal end of AraC tightly binds to the rest of its domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>in The alternate states of AraC occupancy depicted Fig. 4 represent a dynamic equilibrium , governed by the liganddependent changes in AraC conformation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>The striking parallels between AraC and MelR led us to consider whether the light switch model applies to MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The isogenic AraC + and AraC - strains were SH322 and SH321 ( 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3041410" target="_blank">3041410</a>]<br></li>
<li>The extent of AraC stimulation of araBAD is at least 25-fold larger .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>The preference of AraC to loop was also revealed in calculations of the expression levels of pBAD under a wide variety conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>The location of one of these regions is precisely aligned with the ChIP-seq peak , suggesting that this sequence is bound by AraC under the conditions tested .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Strains used were the AraC - strain SH321 , and its isogenic part , ner AraC * SH322 ( Hahn st al. .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Strains used were the AraC - strain SH321 , its isogenic partner AraC ' SH322 , F + SH322 ( called DL100 ) , and AraC ' cya - SH326 ( 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2643114" target="_blank">2643114</a>]<br></li>
<li>In strain SH321 , F DaraC-1022 Dlac74 galK strr12 pWR03 was used to screen AraC mutants for induction at p on arabinose/tetrazolium inBAD 7 dicator plates , as well as for quantitation of induction at 13 pBAD using the arabinose isomerase assay .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>In strain þ r Dlac araD , pWR03 was used to measure the level of repression at pC in AraC mutants .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose is added , looping is reduced and AraC primarily binds to the two adjacent half-sites , I1 and I2 , where it activates transcription from pBAD ( Greenblatt & Schleif , 1971 ; Hendrickson & Schleif , 1984 , 1985 ; Lee et al. , 1987 ; Lobell & Schleif , 1990 ; for a review see Schleif , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon induction by L-arabinose , one subunit of AraC releases the distal O2 site and instead binds to the adjacent promoter-proximal site I2 , thereby activating transcription from PBAD ( Lee et al. , 1987 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araBAD promoter , CRP binds to a site upstream of AraC Sites I1 and I2 , and this binding is independent of the binding of AraC ( Zhang and Schleif , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araFGH promoter , however , the orientation of the sites is reversed as compared with those of the other ara promoters ; the CRP site is adjacent to that for RNA polymerase , and AraC binds upstream of CRP ( Fig. 1 ) ( 29 ) , whereas at araBAD AraC binds adjacent to polymerase and CRP binds upstream ( 48 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , whereas AraC binds as a dimer ( 15 ) to a direct repeat of the ; 17-bp sequence ( 6 , 7 ) , Rob and SoxS bind their targets as monomers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>]<br></li>
<li>A dimer of AraC binds to the operators I1 and O2 in the repressing state ( N and C denote the N and C-terminal domains of AraC , respectively ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although AraC binds this site with high affinity , its function is not known .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose binds to AraC in a pocket located within a â-barrel ( Figure 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>araI1 * binds AraC considerably more tightly than araI2 binds AraC ( 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC directly binds the PxylA promoter region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>Collectively , these results demonstrate that AraC binds the P promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION The uptake and metabolism of arabinose are believed to involve eight proteins : AraE , a low-afﬁnity transporter ; AraF , AraG , and AraH , which constitute the high-afﬁnity transport system ; AraB , AraA , and AraD , the three enzymes necessary for arabinose metabolism ; and AraC , the major transcriptional-regulator of the regulon ( 34 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10094697" target="_blank">10094697</a>]<br></li>
<li>When the inducer is absent , araBAD and araC are repressed by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon addition of the inducer , AraC becomes an activator of the araBAD operon while continuing to repress the araC gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although it is evident that transcription of the xyl promoters is activated by D-xylose , we can not rule out the possibility of a transcriptional repression in the absence of an inducer , as in the case of the araBAD operon that is negatively regulated by AraC and DNA looping .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9371449" target="_blank">9371449</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araBAD and melAB promoters AraC and MelR bind to alternative sites in the absence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>According to this model , there are striking similarities in the regulation of the E. coli melR ± melAB and araC ± araBAD genes ; in particular both MelR and AraC can form repression loops in the absence of their cognate inducer ligand .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression in the absence of inducer can be kept to very low levels in the presence of glucose , because of the repressor activity of AraC and the reduced concentration of cyclic AMP , allowing for the cloning of toxic genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10094697" target="_blank">10094697</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is not known whether AraC is bound to araOl in vivo in the absence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it appears that there are two discrete regions , araIl and araI2 , of approximately equal size that differ greatly in their affinity for AraC protein in the absence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>These regions , designated araI1 and araI2 , differ greatly in their affinities for AraC in the absence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of inducer , AraC is locked into cooperative interaction at araI1 a with araO2 , preventing its participation in an araIl/araI2 association .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using the facts that arabinose induces the wildtype system approximately 100 , that this induction is about half of the maximum possible , and that in an O2 deletion strain the basal level is elev-ated about fourfold , we can generate the following requirements : in the presence of arabinose : aDI112 0:5 aDtotal in the absence of arabinose : AB KAB A B D D I112 0:005 tota Numerically solving this system of three equations yields : T 130 ; 000 ; Lÿa 8:3 ; and L a 1:3 O2 strain in the absence of arabin DI112 D DI112 DI1ÿns DI112 D DI1O2 DI112 DI1ÿns plete set of values used in our re as follows : and in a ose : 4 It is noteworthy that the product of T , KI1 and , KI2 yields a value for the true Ka of AraC binding to I1-I2 that is consistent with the best data available from direct measurement ( Hendrickson & Schleif , 1984 ; Carra & Schleif , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>( Top ) In the presence of wild-type AraC , CAP can activate ara pBAD-I1-I1 * about 12-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>( Middle ) In the presence of the AraC DNA binding domain , CAP can also activate transcription from ara pBAD-I1-I1 * about 10-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>CAP does not signiﬁcantly activate pBAD in the absence of AraC ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>To assess possible CAP-AraC interactions in vivo , we compared the amount of AraC binding in the presence and absence of CAP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>We were also not surprised to ﬁnd that RhaS-CTD was capable of equivalent transcription activation in the absence and the presence of L-rhamnose ( data not shown ) , since amino acid sequence alignment with AraC suggests that the RhaS N-terminal domain likely binds L-rhamnose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that the behavior of the AraC dimerization domain in the absence of ligand is best described as an isodesmic , or indefinite selfassociation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>The molecular mechanism of the effector response has been well defined for AraC and its effector L-arabinose , and is referred to as the `` light-switch '' mechanism ( Harmer et al. , 2001 ; Reed and Schleif , 1999 ; Saviola et al. , 1998 ; Wu and Schleif , 2001a , b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>This would be similar to the N-terminal arm that mediates the L-arabinose `` light-switch '' mechanism in AraC ( Harmer et al. , 2001 ; Reed and Schleif , 1999 ; Saviola et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overall , these results suggest that the mechanism of the RhaS L-rhamnose response does not involve an N-terminal arm inhibiting activity in the absence of L-rhamnose , and thereby differs from the AraC L-arabinose response .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although AraC R251 ( in the DNA binding domain of AraC ) has been proposed to interact with residues in the N-terminal arm of AraC in the absence of L-arabinose ( Wu and Schleif , 2001b ) , suggesting that RhaR might use a similar mechanism , our results suggest that the RhaR L-rhamnose response is not similar to the AraC light-switch mechanism ( Saviola et al. , 1998 ; Wu and Schleif , 2001b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>( 1991 ) 218 , 45-54 AraC-DNA Looping : Orientation and Distance-dependent Loop Breaking by the Cyclic MP Receptor Protein A Robert B. Lobe117 Department of Biochemistry Brandeis University , Waltham , MA 02254 , U.S.A. and Robert F. Schleif Department of Biology Johns Hopkins I 'n iversity , 34th a , nd Charles St , Baltimore , MD 21218 , U.S.A. ( Received 29 May 1990 ; accepted 22 October 1990 ) The arabinose operon promoter , pBAD , is negatively regulated in the absence of arabinose by AraC protein , which forms a DNA loop by binding to t , wo sites separated by 210 base-pairs , arao , and aral , .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848302" target="_blank">1848302</a>]<br></li>
<li>Department of Biology Johns Hopkins University 3400 N. Charles Street Baltimore , MD 21218 , USA # 1998 Academic Press Limited * Corresponding author Introduction Keywords : AraC ; DNA looping ; relative af ® nities ; gene expression ; partition function In the absence of arabinose , the dimeric regulator of the ara pBAD promoter , AraC , forms a DNA loop between the I1 and O2 half-sites ( Figure 1 ) that represses activity of pBAD ( Dunn et al. , 1984 ; Hahn et al. , 1984 ; Martin et al. , 1986 ; Huo et al. , 1988 ; Lee & Schleif , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Biochemistry 2000 , 39 , 11593-11601 11593 Characterization of the Oligomeric States of Wild Type and Mutant AraC † Nicole LaRonde-LeBlanc ‡ and Cynthia Wolberger * , ‡ , § Howard Hughes Medical Institute and Department of Biophysics and Biophysical Chemistry , Johns Hopkins UniVersity School of Medicine , 725 North Wolfe Street , Baltimore , Maryland 21205-2185 ReceiVed June 1 , 2000 ; ReVised Manuscript ReceiVed July 20 , 2000 ABSTRACT : AraC regulates transcription of the Escherichia coli arabinose operon , binding tandem DNA half-sites in the presence of arabinose and widely spaced half-sites in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Structure and Properties of a Truely Apo Form of AraC Dimerization Domain John E. Weldon , Michael E. Rodgers , Christopher Larkin , and Robert F. Schleif * Department of Biology , Johns Hopkins University , Baltimore , Maryland ABSTRACT The arabinose-binding pockets of wild type AraC dimerization domains crystallized in the absence of arabinose are occupied with the side chains of Y31 from neighboring domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>With AraC , the non-DNA-binding domain is known to-bind the inducer arabinose , and this ligand binding converts AraC from a repressor to a transcriptional-activator ( reviewed by Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12791142" target="_blank">12791142</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N terminus ( up to residue 170 ) allows AraC to form stable dimers and binds the inducer L-arabinose ; the C-terminal residues 178 to 286 comprise the minimal DNA-binding and activating domain ( Eustance et al. , 1994 ; Menon & Lee , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The latter has seemed more likely as AraC , which consists of functionally independent dimerization-arabinose binding and DNA binding-transcription activation domains ( Bustos & Schleif , 1993 ) , has been postulated on the basis of the crystal structures in the presence and absence of arabinose and aggregation properties ( Soisson et al. , 1997 ) to change the separ-ation between the attachment points for the DNA binding domains through an arabinose regulated change in the dimerization interface .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N-terminal arm binds over the L-arabinose binding pocket in the presence of L-arabinose ( Soisson et al. , 1997b ) , leaving the two AraC domains in each monomer flexibly connected , and allowing transcription activation from the araBAD promoter-proximal halfsites ( Harmer et al. , 2001 ; Seabold and Schleif , 1998 ; Wu and Schleif , 2001a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon addition of the inducer L-arabinose ( represented by ﬁlled circles ) , AraC undergoes a conformational change that makes long-distance looping impossible and so restricts binding to the proximal target sites I1 and I2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that L-arabinose increases the binding of one AraC subunit to the I1 target in a manner analogous to how tryptophan increases the binding of Trp repressor to trp operator ( Schevitz et al. , 1985 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose is present , the binding of a monomeric AraC shifts to araI2 ( located toward PBAD as part of araI ) from araO2 , thereby activating the transcription of PBAD ( 3 , 20 , 29 , 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9371449" target="_blank">9371449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon the introduction of arabinose , AraC undergoes a ligand-induced conformational change that precludes its cooperative binding to araI1 and araO2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>The conformational change in AraC induced by the binding of L-arabinose ( 28 ) is necessary for its cooperative binding to araI and araI2 , which produces araBAD activation ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>The more upstream conserved sequence that resembles an AraC binding site falls outside the region predicted by the ChIP-seq data ; hence , it may bind AraC under other growth conditions , e.g. , in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose binds to AraC , the filling of the sugar binding pocket and folding of the N-terminal arm over the sugar close off the â-barrel interface , leaving only the coiled-coil interface to mediate dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding of arabinose to AraC closes off the â-barrel interface , leaving only the coiled-coil interface available for dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Three relevant states of AraC binding are depicted , a looped state with AraC binding to ara0 , and aral , , an unlooped state with AraC-arabinose binding to aral , and aral , .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848302" target="_blank">1848302</a>]<br></li>
<li>We used a high concentration of L-rhamnose in the binding buffer since , in the analogous ura system , K , , , for L-arabinose binding to AraC is 5 x 10M3 ~ ( Wilcox , 1974 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2405166" target="_blank">2405166</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is particularly important for AraC binding upstream of ydeN , since this interaction appears to be completely dependent upon arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>There is considerable evidence , however , suggesting that the requirement for arabinose in the allosteric transition of AraC is not absolute and that a very small amount of AraC activator is present even in the uninduced cell ( 7 , 31 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>In other words , we tested whether AraC mutants that do not require arabinose to activate the P promoter also repress P araB xylA promoter activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , we conclude that intracellular arabinose is not inhibiting the activity of XylR but rather is repressing PxylA promoter activity through the action of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>This promoter is under the cmítrol of the AraC repressor and expression is induced with arabinose ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9125116" target="_blank">9125116</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , araBAD is only moderately regulated by CRP and can be substantially induced by arabinose-AraC alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC is functional as a dimer ; in the presence of arabinose , the conformation of AraC is such that the two subunits of the dimer bind to two adjacent target sites resulting in activation of the araBAD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Model of AraC induction by L-arabinose at the araBAD promoter and relevant sites at the divergent araC promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Model of AraC induction by L-arabinose at the araBAD promoter ( PBAD ) , according to Lobell & Schleif ( 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , AraC protein bound at the araI site , which is immediately adjacent to the RNA polymerase binding site of the PBAD promoter , stimulates transcription of the araBAD genes ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3041410" target="_blank">3041410</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the MerR protein represses merT when it is unliganded and activates transcription of merT when mercury is bound ( 109 ) , and similar effects of arabinose binding are observed in the regulation of araBAD by AraC ( 88 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7968922" target="_blank">7968922</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC activates the arabinose-catabolism genes araAB , araE , and araFGH , and suppresses the xylose-catabolism genes xylAB and xylFGH by inhibiting XylR , the xylose transcriptional-activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26045332" target="_blank">26045332</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vivo , as well as in vitro ( 11 , 18 ) , transcription from pJ is dependent upon the arabinose-specific transcriptional-regulator protein AraC and the global catabolite gene activator protein CAP , as is transcription from the araBAD , araE , and araFGH ( 7 , 8 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1744033" target="_blank">1744033</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of L-arabinose , AraC acts as a transcriptional-activator for the araBAD , araFGH and araE promoters , as well as for the araJ promoter serving a gene of an obscure function .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11750821" target="_blank">11750821</a>]<br></li>
<li>E. coli AraC activates transcription of the araBAD , araFGH , araE , and araJ transcripts in the presence of its inducer , L-arabinose ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , AraC protein activates the expression of the araBAD , araFGH , and araE promoters ( 6-10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of L-arabinose , AraC activates expression of araBAD , araE , and araFGH ( 4 , 14 , 20 , 23 , 24 , 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>With arabinose , AraC activates transcription from the promoters of the catabolic operons ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>When bound with arabinose , AraC activates the transcription of the araBAD , araE , and araFGH operons and represses transcription from the araC operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose is added , the subunit that formerly contacted araO2 releases and shifts to the araI2 half-site , from which it activates transcription from the araBAD promoter ( PBAD ) ( 19 ) , results that extend a prior observation that the presence of arabinose can extend the region of aral2 that AraC protects from DNase I digestion ( 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon induction of arabinose , AraC releases the upstream araO2 half-site and binds to the downstream araI1-araI2 site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>These chimeras functioned well in vivo and in vitro , and here we show that AraC contains functional domains for dimerization , arabinose binding , DNA binding , and activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Are direct arm-arabinose interactions the sole effector of the arms ' positioning and hence , the regulatory properties of AraC , or do changes in the dimerization/arabinosebinding domain also contribute to control of the arm or DNA binding domain positions ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>' Analysis of the mutations within the AraC binding site , aruFG1 , aredescribed in this report.After mutagenesis , DNA was transformed into strain WH75 , and thepromoteractivity of cells was screened by the color reaction on MacConkey , arabinose , and galactose plates .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the strength of this interaction would be insufficient to be consistent with the dimer-switch model , leading us to conclude that this does not constitute a likely mechanism for arabinose-regulated DNA binding by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>They have proposed that the DNA loop formed in the presence of L-arabinose involves AraC bound to the araOl and araO2 sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA loop models propose that in the absence of L-arabinose a loop is formed between AraC bound at the araI site and the araO2 site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC NTD binds to the CTD and holds the CTD in a conformation favoring DNA looping in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose was added , AraC bound DNA and G ( 239 ) and G ( 260 ) became hypersensitive to DMS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Dimerization occurs between adjacent DNA sites when AraC binds arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , our data suggest that the overall afﬁnity of AraC for its DNA sites is increased by association with arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of L-arabi-nose , the binding of AraC to araI1 was reduced to one-sixth or less .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , the AraC dimer represses the ara'BAD promoter by binding at the distal ara02and the promoter-proximal aral site , thereby forming a DNA loop and occluding RNA polymerase from the promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8087856" target="_blank">8087856</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of L-arabinose we observed a sixfold reduction of binding of AraC to araI1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In both the presence and absence of arabinose , the footprint by AraC was the same as on the promoter without the CAP binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC favors binding to half-sites separated by more than one helical turn of DNA ( Fig. 3 ) , whereas in the presence of arabinose , AraC favors binding to half-sites separated by less than one helical turn of DNA ( 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>As discussed below , these results indicate that the orientations of the DNA binding domains of AraC are constrained in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , genetic , physiological , and physical experiments suggest or are consistent with the arms binding to the DNA-binding domains 1 -- 3,7,8 of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>Apo-AraC Actively Seeks to Loop Robert R. Seabold and Robert F. Schleif * In the absence of arabinose and interactions with other proteins , AraC , the activator-repressor that regulates the araBAD operon in Escherichia coli , was found to prefer participating in DNA looping interactions between the two well-separated DNA half-sites , araI1 and araO2 at their normal separation of 211 base-pairs rather than binding to these same two half-sites when they are adjacent to one another .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the minus arabinose repressing state , left , the AraC DNA binding domains are held in a position that favors looping by binding to the two widely separated DNA half-sites araO2 and araI1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , the arms bind more tightly over the sugar , freeing the DNA binding domains to-bind to the araI1 and araI2 half-sites , from which position AraC stimulates activity of the pBAD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it has been suggested that L-arabinose stabilises the form of AraC that is capable of forming a complex with the neighbouring sequences I1 and I2 , and that in the absence of L-arabinose AraC adopts a conformation that is capable of forming a loop over longer distances ( Lobell & Schleif , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in the absence of - arabinose , the loop L complex between AraC and the B-boxes of and O2 I1 is favoured .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is also a single AraC genes necessary for uptake and catabolism dimer that binds to the I1-I2 site in the of arabinose ( 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , arabinose converts AraC from a form that binds to distal targets ( O2 and I1 ) to a form that binds to adjacent targets ( I1 and I2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus L-arabinose is necessary for AraC to-bind tightly to the A-boxes in I1 and I2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of L-arabinose , the nearby I2 forms a stronger complex with its A-box and AraC than the B-box of O2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC dimer binds the operator sequence I1-I2 tightly in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , AraC binds to I2 , which is adjacent to I1 , rather than to O2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , in the presence of L-arabinose , AraC binds with one subunit to I1 and with the other subunit to I2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC binds as a dimer to two separated DNA sites ( denoted O2 and I1 ) at the araBAD promoter , but is unable to occupy a third crucial site ( I2 , adjacent to I1 ) that overlaps the 235 region , and which must be occupied for activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , at the araC promoter , separate and distinct DNA sites for AraC , Sites O1 and O2 , are required for autoregulation in the absence and presence of arabinose respectively ( Schleif , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the work described here we have measured the relative af ® nity of AraC protein for the halfsites relevant to pBAD expression , I1 , I2 , O2 , and non-speci ® c DNA in the presence and absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabi - presence of arabinose and to the widely nose , a single AraC dimer contacts the two separated I1 and O2 sites in the absence of widely separated I1 and O2 half-sites , form - arabinose ( 4 , 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC , in the absence of arabinose , loops out the intervening DNA between I1 and O2 preventing induction , and in the presence of arabinose , AraC binds the adjacent I1 and I2 half-sites and activates pBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , we measured the relative af ® nities of AraC for the I1 , O2 , and I2 half-sites as well as for nonspeci ® c DNA in the presence and absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>As re ¯ ected in the relative occupancies of the two half-sites , in the absence of arabinose , ( Figure 4 ( a ) ) , AraC does indeed prefer to loop , and in the presence of arabinose , it prefers to-bind cis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the addition of arabinose , AraC preferred to-bind to the adjacently located half-sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of arabinose induces conformational changes in AraC that lead it to-bind to two adjacent half-sites , araI1 and araI2 ( 24 , 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , both the MelR and AraC proteins bind to their cognate sites in both the presence and the absence of the cognate activator ( arabinose and melibiose respectively ) ( Webster et al. , 1989 ; Lobell & Schleif , 1991 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC , one of the members in Group 2 , is suggested to-bind to at least two sites around the promoter region and to form a double stranded DNA loop of more than 200 bp in the absence of arabinose , cAMP or CRP , while the loop could open in the presence of both arabinose and cAMP-CRP ( Dunn et al. , 1984 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8729576" target="_blank">8729576</a>]<br></li>
<li>Measurements were performed in the absence of arabinose Protein expressed units None ( strain only ) 160 None ( + pBR322 ) 175 AraC 10 16 AraCDNA 120 1 ZipDimer-AraCDNA 12 13 Plasmids expressing the indicated proteins were transformed into the AraC operator strain SH242 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , unlike the PhoP regulon , most AraC regulatory targets are conserved across related species , although conservation is limited to genes required for the transport and metabolism of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lee SK , Chou HH , Pfleger BF , Newman JD , Yoshikuni Y , Keasling JD ( 2007 ) Directed evolution of AraC for improved compatibility of arabinose - and lactose-inducible promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25420677" target="_blank">25420677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Directed evolution of AraC for improved compatibility of arabinose - and lactose-inducible promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26070674" target="_blank">26070674</a>]<br></li>
<li>We found a shift of at most 1 or 2 bp DISCUSSION The L-arabinose operon of E. coli has long been known to be positively and negatively regulated by AraC ( 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2643114" target="_blank">2643114</a>]<br></li>
<li>The implications of these results for the mechanism of AraC induction by L-arabinose are discussed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The mechanisms by which these genes are indirectly regulated by AraC and/or arabinose are unclear .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The inducer for AraC is arabinose and for MelR , melibiose but both these sugars are taken up by permeases producing free sugar in the cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ability of arabinose to act as an inducer of transcriptional activation is blocked by D-fucose , which is a competitive inhibitor of AraC ( 7-9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The I2 site overlaps the 35 element of paraBAD , and AraC normally occupies this site only in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of tyrosine in the pocket could drive AraC from a true apo-structure to the one observed , one that is virtually identical to the arabinose-bound structure .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>We used RNA-seq to determine the effects of AraC and arabinose on genome-wide RNA levels in S. enterica .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , ydeNM is a novel AraC-regulated operon that is directly repressed by AraC in an arabinose-dependent manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutations altering the speci-ﬁcity of AraC from its cognate inducer L-arabinose to D-arabinose and fucose have been identiﬁed ( 58 , 63 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22797760" target="_blank">22797760</a>]<br></li>
<li>Only one indirect target gene , isrB , is upregulated 4-fold by both AraC and arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effects of AraC and arabinose on global gene expression in S. enterica .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data suggest that AraC regulates functions beyond arabinose metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>ygeA and polB are positively regulated by AraC and arabinose due to partial read-through of Rho-independent terminators ( Fig. 2 , 4 , and 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>No direct targets were identiﬁed that are regulated by AraC in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genes regulated indirectly by arabinose and AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>All of the direct regulatory targets are positively regulated by AraC and arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We systematically substituted every base-pair in a synthetic araI1 target with the three possible alternatives and then tested binding of araI1 and of these 51 DNA targets to AraC by quantitative gel shift analysis in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>1 2 Results Recognition of mutant araI1 DNA targets by wild-type AraC To identify the bases speciﬁcally contacted by AraC , we synthesised a suitable wild-type araI1 target and examined the effects of all possible single base-pair substitutions upon AraC binding in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cells transformed with mutagenized DNA were plated in the presence of arabinose to screen for down mutations and plated without arabinose to look for any up mutations that are independent of AraC activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both DNA targets are shifted by AraC in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>To sum up , we suggest that L-arabinose increases the binding of AraC to the A-box more than to the B-box of its DNA target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that the DNA binding properties of AraC allow it to-bind at ydeN only in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of L-arabinose , substitution of a speciﬁcally contacted base should have a drastic effect on the AraC afﬁnity for its target , whereas substitutions at non-contacted bases should have weak or no effects .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusive evidence for effector binding and dimerization of AraC in this nonconserved domain is provided by the crystal structure of this domain in the presence of arabinose ( 232 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>From measurements of AraC binding , the presence of arabinose increases the af ® nity about 40-fold , thus Ca 40 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with our ChIP data showing binding of AraC upstream of ydeN only in the presence of arabinose ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results demonstrate that apo-AraC possesses an intrinsic looping preference that is eliminated by the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>We then compared the fractional saturation of the various targets by AraC in gel mobility shift assays , in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
