<li>Discussion How does AraC repress the BAD operon in the absence of L-arabinose and how does it activate the BAD operon in the presence of L-arabinose ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC is a dimer in both the presence and the absence of arabinose ( 255 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Possible model of AraC binding to its natural targets in the presence or absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , the arms bind to the dimerization domains of AraC over the bound arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>As an activator , AraC in the presence of arabinose enhances expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7836283" target="_blank">7836283</a>]<br></li>
<li>It can be seen that AraC shifts the araIid target in the presence of L-arabinose quite well .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>ChIP/qPCR veriﬁed signiﬁcant association of AraC with all regions tested in the presence of arabinose ( Fig. 1A ; araJ was not tested ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Association of AraC with all regions was reduced in the absence of arabinose , with no association detected for ydeN ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , we did not detect AraC association upstream of ydeN ( Fig. 1A ) , nor did we detect any signiﬁcant difference in expression of ydeN or ydeM between wild-type and araC mutant cells in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine whether the AraC site within E. coli dcp is associated with transcription regulation , we used ChIP/qPCR to measure association of RNAP in the presence and absence of arabinose in a wild-type and a araC strain ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike the wild-type control , which showed repression by AraC in the presence and absence of inducer ( Table 1 , lines 1-3 ) , the araO1259 lysogen showed a complete loss of autoregulation in the presence of arabinose ( Table 1 , line 6 ) , whereas the normal repression ( by a factor of 10 ) was observed in the absence of the sugar ( Table 1 , line 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
