<li>A dimer of AraC protein contacts three adjacent major groove regions of the araI DNA site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3275618" target="_blank">3275618</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10802742" target="_blank">10802742</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Thus , the extended -10 motif of ParaF is not sufficient for constitutive activity ; AraC , and possibly CRP , must still provide some structure for efficient polymerase recognition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
