<li>Here , we used two complementary genomic approaches to comprehensively identify members of the AraC regulon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , our data indicate that most members of the AraC regulon are conserved in this family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Most of the homology between RhaR and AraC was also confined to the C terminus of the two proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3316663" target="_blank">3316663</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is interesting to note that most of the homology between AraC , RhaS and RhaR is found in the C terminus , perhaps the two rha proteins bind their target sites using a similar sequence located in their C termini .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3316663" target="_blank">3316663</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , we found that I1 consists of two separate regions in which speciﬁc contacts to AraC occur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , we located the two regions in AraC that interact with the A-box or the B-box , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Oligomeric States of the Mutated AraC N-Terminal Domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
