<li>Ross JJ , Gryczynski U , Schleif R. Mutational analysis of residue roles in AraC function .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Consistent with this , neither AraC nor Ada have a negatively charged residue that aligns with RhaS D241 , and in both of these cases s70 R599A was not defective for activation ( 33 , 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>Residue 1 corresponds to residue 175 in the native AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>Residue K593 was also found to be important for activation by AraC , but R599 was not ( 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>We constructed three AraC mutants in both putative HTH-motifs by site-speciﬁc mutagenesis , substituting alanine for the original residues ( see Figure 2 ( a ) ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fully assigned 1H-15N-HSQC spectrum of the DBD containing residues 175 -- 281 of AraC is shown in Supplementary Figure 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>The residues shown in bold were individually replaced by alanine to obtain the AraC mutants Ser208Ala , His212Ala and Asp256Ala , which were used in retardation assays ( see Figure 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , there is one nucleotide within araI2 that appears to affect both AraC and polymerase functions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine whether the alpha subunit is essential for open-complex formation at pFGH , as it is at many promoters , we measured the amount of open complex formed when an RNA polymerase containing truncated alpha subunits ( 12 ) is used in the presence or absence of AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>CAP and AraC act cooperatively to stimulate open-complex formation by assisting very tight binding of RNA polymerase to pFGH , and AraC appears to contact the C-terminal domain of the alpha subunit of RNA polymerase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result suggests that at pFGH , RNA polymerase interacts with AraC protein via the C-terminal domain of the a subunit .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similar assays with RNA polymerase containing truncated alpha subunits suggest that AraC interacts with the C-terminal domain of the alpha subunit .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , our work suggests that AraC at pFGH makes important contacts with the C-terminal domain of the alpha subunit of RNA polymerase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our conclusions with respect to contacts with the RNA polymerase s subunit are fully consistent with others ' results with AraC , RhaS , etc. mentioned above .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Does RNA polymerase contact CAP and , in addition , contact AraC so that both proteins directly assist binding or isomerization , or does AraC activate transcription by some mechanism other than direct contact with RNA polymerase ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>In light of the strict spacing and orientation requirements for AraC activation , interactions between AraC and RNA polymerase are likely to be speciﬁc and inﬂexible .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Occupation of I2 results in transcription-activation , presumably because AraC bound at I2 is able to interact directly with the RNA polymerase s subunit bound to the 235 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the case of paraBAD it has been shown that this overlap is essential for transcription-activation , most likely because AraC ( and presumably XylS , RhaR and RhaS at their targets ) makes direct contact with the RNA polymerase σ subunit that is docking to the ® 35 hexamer [ 20 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>They found that all but one of the linker amino acids could be substituted by other amino acids individually and in small groups with no substantial effect on the ability of AraC protein to activate transcription when arabinose is present .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>the presence of arabinose , AraC protein assumes a conformation that can stimulate the function of RNA polymerase ( 13 , 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The region containing nucleotides -38 , -39 , and -40 , normally protected by AraC protein in the presence of arabinose , was completely exposed to DNase I digestion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>This study , as well as a previous report ( 13 ) , documents that the wild-type AraC protein in the absence of arabinose forms a dimer with some residual formation of higher-order multimers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>In t.he absence of arabinose , most copies of the ara regulatory region in vivo contain a loop between ara0 , and araI mediated by AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been shown that an AraC dimer forms a DNA-protein-DNA loop in the absence of L-arabinose ( Lobell & Schleif , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , in the presence of L-arabinose , AraC binds with one subunit to I1 and with the other subunit to I2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , the arms bind to the dimerization domains of AraC over the bound arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>As re ¯ ected in the relative occupancies of the two half-sites , in the absence of arabinose , ( Figure 4 ( a ) ) , AraC does indeed prefer to loop , and in the presence of arabinose , it prefers to bind cis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>The values determined for the unknown par-ameters reveal that , in the absence of arabinose , AraC possesses a substantial preference to loop between two well-separated half-sites rather than bind to two adjacent half-sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabi - presence of arabinose and to the widely nose , a single AraC dimer contacts the two separated I1 and O2 sites in the absence of widely separated I1 and O2 half-sites , form - arabinose ( 4 , 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC contacts the arah half-site and the araO2 half-site of the araBAD regulatory region , forming a DNA loop between the two ( Fig. 1 ) ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The second dimer-interface in the uncomplexed AraC crystals ( Fig. 3B ) brings together two b barrels , in a face-to-face manner , and buries 75 % more area than the coiled-coil interface , giving a total of 2100 Å2 of buried surface area .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of bound ligand opens a second , â-barrel interaction interface that also mediates interactions between unliganded AraC dimers in the crystal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the unlig-anded protein , however , a distortion in the top of helix 2 slightly reorients the leucine triad at the ends of the coiled-coil , resulting in an approximate 13 ° rotation of one monomer relative to the other as compared with the coiled-coil dimer formed by AraC with bound arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>According to that model , AraC dimerizes exclusively via the coiled-coil interface , with arabinose serving as a ligand that modulates the conformation of the N-terminal arm of the protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>One of the two dimer-interfaces in the crystals of the unliganded protein reproduces nearly the same coiled-coil interaction seen in the crystals of arabinose-bound AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC with bound arabinose crystallizes as a dimer , with the C-terminal R-helixes from each of two monomers associating to form an antiparallel coiled-coil interface ( Figure 1B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>( A ) AraC dimer with bound arabinose dimerizing via the coiled-coil interface .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Dimerization of the unliganded protein via the â-barrel interface in the absence of interactions mediated by the coiled-coil interface is assayed using a mutant AraC protein with a disrupted coiled-coil interface .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since no self-association is detected in the quadruply mutated AraC protein , the interactions that give rise to slight aggregation of the wild-type protein must depend on prior formation of the coiled-coil dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although two-helix antiparallel coiledcoils between two monomers are relatively rare , the coiled-coil seen in the AraC arab-inose dimer is remarkably similar to the coiled-coil seen in the MetJ-DNA complex ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>Crystallographic data for the N-terminal domain of AraC showed that the two monomers are associated by an antiparallel coiled coil formed between the terminal a-helix of each monomer , with each end of the coiled coil anchored by a triad of leucine residues that pack together in a knobs-into-holes manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
