Suzuki , M. , and Brenner , S.E. ( 1995 ) Classiﬁcation of multihelical DNA-binding domains and application to predict the DBD structures of s factor , LysR , OmpR/PhoB , CENP-B , Rap1 and XylS/Ada/AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15255893" target="_blank">15255893</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_226", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>Classiﬁcation of multi-helical DNA-binding domains and application to predict the DBD structures of s factor , LysR , OmpR/PhoB , CENP-B , Rap1 , and XylS/Ada/AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The locations of a ligand-binding cupin fold , consisting of eight - sheet elements ( 5 , 6 ) and a helix-loop-helix dimerization motif , deduced from similarities with AraC and published AraC structures ( 26 , 27 ) , are shown .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The promoter contains two AraC binding sites that arelocated by DNase1 footprinting at 53-100 and 135-173 base pairs upstreamfrom the point of transcription initiation ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The phosphates which interfere in AraC binding are clustered into four groups , also spaced at 10-11-bp intervals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The guanines that appear to be important for binding are conserved among the seven AraC binding sites , which also suggests their importance in proteinrecognition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , we split each binding site into two ; each half-site ( shown in Fig. 11A ) was of sufficient length ( 21 bp ) to allow the binding of the two HTH motifs present in the C-terminal domain of a GadX ( or GadW ) monomer , as in the case of the AraC / XylS-like proteins ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Egan , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>This means that each site provides sufficient nucle-otides to guarantee the binding of both HTH motifs belonging to the C-terminal domain of each subunit in the functional dimer , as reported for other members of the AraC/XylS-family such as AdpA , AraC , MelR and XylS ( Reeder and Schleif , 1993 ; Gonzalez-Perez et al. , 1999 ; Grainger et al. , 2003 ; Yamazaki et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Subcloning the C-terminal domain of MeiR The available evidence suggests that proteins of the MelR/AraC class bind to DNA via a C-terminal DNA-binding domain ( Francklyn & Lee , 1988 ; Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ; Menon & Lee , 1990 ; Ramos et al. , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutations in the C-terminal domain of MeiR Sequence comparisons show that MelR , and other members of the AraC class of proteins , contain two potential helix-turn-helix motifs in the C-terminal half of the sequence ( Henikoff et al. , 1989 ; Tobin & Schleif , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Importantly , both MarA and SoxS are small proteins with 129 and 107 amino acid residues , respectively , and correspond only to the DNA-binding domains of the typical XylS/AraC regulators ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Rhee et al. , 1998 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12791142" target="_blank">12791142</a>]<br></li>
<li>An analysis of MarA by the method of Chou and Fasman ( 4 ) identified two potential helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domains located between amino acid residues 25 and 52 and between residues 79 and 92 , within regions which have conserved residues with the proteins AraC and XylS ( 23 ) ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8383113" target="_blank">8383113</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was recently suggested that AraC might contact target DNA sequences through the two HTH motifs ( 186 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Each of these substitutions destroys one of the two separate DNA-recognition motifs of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is in agreement with the previous ﬁndings that AraC and RhaR also interact with their DNA-binding sites within two major grooves of each half-site ( 3 , 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutational analysis of AraC has identified two regions located in the carboxy terminus that are important for DNA-binding ( Brunelle , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2405166" target="_blank">2405166</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutational studies of the DNA-binding site of AraC ( 33 ) showed that two groups of bases , 8 bp apart , termed the A and the B boxes , are important for protein-binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to study DNA-binding to either the A-box or the B-box , we constructed the double targets depicted in Figure 3 ( a ) , which allow the two subunits of one dimer of AraC to bind simultaneously to either two A-boxes or two B-boxes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>( b ) Alignment of AraC motifs similar to LexA and Myb DNA-binding motifs ( Suzuki & Brenner , 1995 ) 669 Figure 3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>According to one HTH alignment ( Francklyn & Lee , 1988 ; Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ) , AraC is expected to have two DNA-binding motifs , as shown in Figure 2 ( a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>These are the first reported single amino acid changes in MeIR , and although their effects do not provide a direct proof that motif 2 is involved in DNA-binding , they do raise the possibility that MelR differs from AraC , in which changes in the helix-turn-helix corresponding to motif 1 have clearer effects than changes in the sequence corresponding to motif 2 ( Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our localization of all the amino acids necessary for specific DNA-binding restricts the structure that contacts DNA to the second half of AraC but leaves unanswered the role of a second potential helix-turn-helix region that begins at amino acid 256 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC amino acids Ser208 and His212 , which correspond to amino acids 2 and 6 of the DNA-recognition helix of an H-T-H motif , have been shown to make speciﬁc contacts with base pairs within the AraC binding site ( araI ) ( 3 , 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>Vertical arrows indicate amino acid-base pair contacts between AraC H-T-H 1 and its DNA-binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>One DNA-binding motif in AraC has been predicted to be a helix-turn-helix ( H-T-H ) motif consisting of residues 196 to 215 ( 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>We constructed alanine substitutions at four amino acid positions within the recognition helix of a RhaS H-T-H DNA-binding motif proposed based on alignment with AraC ( 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>An additional DNA-binding determinant within the conserved domain of AraC had been suspected and was subsequently proposed to be a second HTH motif ( Niland et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rhee , S. , Martin , R. , Rosner , J. , and Davies , D. ( 1998 ) A novel DNA-binding motif in MarA : the first structure for an AraC family transcriptional activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Evidence that the ﬁrst HTH motif constitutes the DNA-binding motif in AraC is based on the following ﬁndings .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>They conclude that AraC possibly has only one HTH and a second , unknown DNA-binding structure .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The striking sequence similarities between MelR and other members of the AraC class of proteins provide circumstantial evidence that one or other of the two potential helix-turn-helix motifs in MelR may also be involved in binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since amino acids in the C-terminal part of AraC protein are important for DNA-binding ( Francklyn & Lee , 1988 ; Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ; Menon & Lee , 1990 ) , and since sequence similarities are particularly strong at the Ctermini , it is likely that members of the AraC-family share a common DNA-binding structure .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genetic analysis strongly suggests that the C-terminal part of AraC protein is responsible for DNA sequence recognition and that at least one of the two potential helix-turn-helix motifs is involved ( Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ; Menon & Lee , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION Wehave found that the structure of the AraC protein-binding sites is quite different from that observed for several other helix-turn-helix proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC protein was located on one side of four adjacent helix-turn regions of the DNA , and there is evidence that each AraC monomer requires two direct repeats in successive turns of the DNA helix for binding ( 37 , 110 , 158 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Examination of the AraC protein sequence suggests that it belongs to thehelix-turn-helix class of DNA-binding proteins since it contains two possiblehelix-turn-helix motifs ( 24-26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on sequence homology , the predicted AraC protein DNA-binding domain has been suggestedto contain two helix-turn-helix DNA-binding motifs ( 25 , 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Introduction Members of the very large AraC-family of prokaryotic regulatory proteins typically share approximately 20 % sequence identity over their ~ 110 residue DNA-binding domains ( DBD 's ) .1,2 Most members , including AraC , also contain a domain involved in controlling the protein 's activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since MarA and SoxS are members of the AraC class of DNA-binding proteins and are highly homologous to each other in the putative helix-turn-helix domains ( 1 , 4 , 8 , 9 ) , it was of interest to determine whether MarA is also a transcriptional activator and whether its mode of action is similar to that of SoxS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8522515" target="_blank">8522515</a>]<br></li>
<li>The larger buried surface area of the â-barrel interface , as compared with the coiled-coil interface , raised the possibility that proteinprotein interactions mediated by the â-barrel might play a role in ligand-mediated modulation of AraC DNA-binding activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The proposed switch in dimerization interfaces would result in a change in the relative distance between the DNA-binding domains within a single AraC dimer , since dimerization via the â-barrel interface places the C-terminal DNA-binding domain attachment points 60 Å apart , as compared with 37 Å in the coiled-coil dimer ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose binds to AraC , the filling of the sugar binding pocket and folding of the N-terminal arm over the sugar close off the â-barrel interface , leaving only the coiled-coil interface to mediate dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding of arabinose to AraC closes off the â-barrel interface , leaving only the coiled-coil interface available for dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two possible HTH motifs were proposed in the C-terminal domain of AraC ( 78 ) , but contact to DNA was demonstrated only for the ﬁrst ( 27 , 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because of their loose connections through the dimerization domains ( Bustos & Schleif , 1993 ; Carra & Schleif , 1993 ; Eustance et al. , 1994 ; Eustance & Schleif , 1996 ) , it seems highly unlikely that the DNA sequence to which one DNA-binding domain of the dimeric AraC protein binds affects the sequence selectivity of the other DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>If each DNA-binding domain of AraC were held in a ® xed position with respect to its dimerization domain , then the DNA-binding domains would be positioned with the same inverted repeat symmetry as is possessed by the two dimerization domains ( Soisson et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the dimeric regulatory protein of the L-arabinose operon in Escherichia coli , AraC , can bind to two half-sites in a direct repeat orientation or to two half-sites in inverted repeat orientation ( 13 ) , each monomer of the protein is likely to possess significant flexibility and could well consist of a dimerization domain loosely connected to a DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Then , while it is true that AraC is dimeric in vitro ( 32 , 34 ) and normally requires both half-sites for binding to DNA in vivo ( 20 , 27 ) , our experiments could have misidentified the relevant dimerization domain of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Table 1 shows that the LexA DNA-binding domain itself repressed only by a factor of 2 but that fusing this to the C/EBP leucine-zipper dimerization domain or the N-terminal half of AraC led to repression by a factor of 14 or 12 , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>We therefore constructed two types of chimeras utilizing parts of AraC : the AraC N-terminal half fused to the LexA DNA-binding domain and the AraC C-terminal half fused to the leucine-zipper from the eukaryotic transcriptional activator C/EBP ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA was constructed encoding the N-termi-nal half of AraC fused to the LexA DNA-binding domain ( AraCDimer-LexADNA ) , the C-terminal half of AraC fused to the leucine-zipper region of C/EBP ( ZipDimer-AraCDNA ) , and the C/EBP leucine-zipper fused to the LexA DNA-binding domain ( ZiPDimCr-LexADNA ) ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC and XylS , the namesakes of the family , are examples of two-domain family members in which the nonfamily domain functions in both effector-binding and dimerization ( 7 , 19 , 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>There are currently structures available for the DNA-binding domain of two AraC / XylS family proteins , MarA and Rob ( 31 , 46 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC/XylS-family consists of more than 130 proteins that are identiﬁed by a 99-amino-acid region of sequence similarity within the DNA-binding domain of AraC ( 17 , 18 , 44 , 53 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA encoding the AraC DNA-binding domain region , amino acid residues 175 -- 292 , was inserted between the Nco1 and Sac1 sites in the multiple cloning region in the pET24d vector .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>MarA and its homolog SoxS are unique among AraC proteins in that they have only the DNA-binding domain ( 129 and 107 amino acid residues , respectively ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>The possibility of intermolecular domain swapping40 of the helix-turn-helix subdodmains of AraC DBD appears compatible with the very weak interdomain interactions between the two helix-turn-helix regions as well as the likelihood that in the process of binding to DNA , one of the helix-turn-helix regions in the AraC DBD undergoes considerable rotation with respect to the other helix-turn-helix region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , the solution structure of the DNA-binding domain of AraC contains two weakly interacting helix-turn-helix regions connected by an α-helix .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>The finding that the fusion protein efficiently repressed the AraCDimer-LexADNA expression of PSUIA-lacZ , whereas the LexA DNA-binding domain alone did not , suggested that the addition of the AraC dimerization region did indeed dimerize the chimeric protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dimerization capability provided by the leucine-zipper region of C/EBP in ZiPpimerAraCDNA permits the AraC DNA-binding domain to bind to the araO , site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding of the arm is postulated to constrain the DNA-binding domain in an orientation that causes the AraC dimer to favor binding to the widely spaced I1 and O2 sites , thereby looping out the intervening DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The promoter activity was measured by the b-galactosidase assay in SH322 cells or in SH321 cells with the AraC DNA-binding domain expressed from plasmid pGBO21B .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC DNA-binding domain consists of seven alpha helices in two weakly interconnected subdomains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>The proposed DNA-binding motifs in the AraC C terminus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has previously been shown that an overexpressed DNA-binding domain of AraC could weakly activate transcription ( 7 ) , indicating that this domain of AraC is capable of transcription-activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>( Middle ) In the presence of the AraC DNA-binding domain , CAP can also activate transcription from ara pBAD-I1-I1 * about 10-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Are direct arm-arabinose interactions the sole effector of the arms ' positioning and hence , the regulatory properties of AraC , or do changes in the dimerization/arabinosebinding domain also contribute to control of the arm or DNA-binding domain positions ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mapping arm-DNA-binding domain interactions in AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22797760" target="_blank">22797760</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
