<li>Wu M , Schleif R. Mapping arm-DNA-binding domain interactions in AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Because several members of the family possess this property and because the dimerization domain of AraC is soluble ( 232 ) , it seems that it is the DNA-binding domain which makes these proteins poorly soluble ( 64 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fusing the DNA-binding domain of AraC to a heterologous dimerization domain could generate chimeric proteins capable of binding to a normal AraC binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="DOM_collapse_similarity" for="dom_similarity_298">
Timmes A , Rodgers ME , Schleif R. Biochemical and physiological properties of the DNA-binding domain of AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_298", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>Biochemical and physiological properties of the DNA-binding domain of AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Analogously , a dimerization domain from AraC could potentiate the specific binding by a DNA-binding domain from another , normally dimeric , protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC protein is composed of a dimerization domain and a DNA-binding domain ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>To date , however , despite intense effort , x-ray structure determinations of either AraC or its DNA-binding domain have been unsuccessful .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>Initial NMR studies of the DNA-binding domain of AraC suggested that the C-terminal portion of the domain is unstructured .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that at least in the case of AraC , the ligand domain and the DNA-binding domain are independent ( 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>To rule out this possibility , we used just the DNA-binding domain of AraC ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Another example is the DNA-binding domain of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>pGBO21B expresses the AraC DNA-binding domain ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION The experiments described here show that functional chi-meric proteins be constructed in which either their can dimerization and arabinose-responsive abilities derive from the N-terminal half of AraC protein or their DNA-binding and transcription-activation abilities originate from the C-termi-nal half of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , functional chimeras have been constructed in which the N-terminal half of AraC provided dimerization and arabinose responsiveness and the C-terminal half provided binding and transcription-activation capabilities .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>To explain this , Schleif and his colleagues proposed the light switch model ( 23 , 24 ) , which was derived from X-ray structural analyses of the AraC N-terminal arabinose-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although AraC R251 ( in the DNA-binding domain of AraC ) has been proposed to interact with residues in the N-terminal arm of AraC in the absence of L-arabinose ( Wu and Schleif , 2001b ) , suggesting that RhaR might use a similar mechanism , our results suggest that the RhaR L-rhamnose response is not similar to the AraC light-switch mechanism ( Saviola et al. , 1998 ; Wu and Schleif , 2001b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Residues 7 to 18 of AraC constitute an NH2-terminal arm that lies across the sugar-binding pocket , fully enclosing the arabinose molecule within the b-barrel domain ( Fig. 2A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>These studies ( 26 , 27 ) showed that the AraC N-terminal domain contains a cupin fold that carries the binding site for arabinose and that the extreme N-terminal arm ( AraC residues 1 to 20 ) folds over bound arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The structure of the N-terminal domain of AraC ( 13 ) revealed several features thought to be important to the mechanism of arabinose-mediated switching of AraC binding site preferences ( Figure 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N terminus ( up to residue 170 ) allows AraC to form stable dimers and binds the inducer L-arabinose ; the C-terminal residues 178 to 286 comprise the minimal DNA-binding and activating domain ( Eustance et al. , 1994 ; Menon & Lee , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Nterminal AraC domain is responsible for both dimerization and L-arabinose binding , while the C-terminal domain is responsible for both DNA-binding and transcription-activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N-terminal domain of AraC ( residues 1-167 ) binds arabinose and mediates dimerization , while the C-terminal domain ( residues 178-292 ) binds DNA ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicate that an arabinose-binding site is located in the dimerization domain in the N-terminal half of AraC and that this domain undergoes a change upon the addition of arabinose that affects the DNA-binding properties of a heterologous DNA-binding domain attached by a linker .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , a ﬂexible inter-domain linker allows AraC to bind adjacent , tandem sites when arabinose frees the DNA-binding domains of AraC from the constraints imposed by the 2-fold symmetry dimer core formed by the dimerization domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15491603" target="_blank">15491603</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , arabinose binding to the N-terminal domain of AraC alters the conformation of the protein such that it is forced to bind to the adjacent sites , I1 and I2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vivo and in vitro experiments showed that a chimeric protein consisting of the N-terminal half of the AraC protein and the DNA-binding domain of the LexA repressor dimerizes , binds to a LexA operator , and represses the expression of a LexA operator in an arabinose-responsive manner ( 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N-terminal domain alone is capable of mediating an arabinose response , as seen by the ability of a chimeric protein containing the N-terminal domain of AraC fused to a LexA-DNA-binding-domain to respond to arabinose ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>The light switch model proposes that , in the absence of arabinose , the interaction of the AraC N-terminal arm with the C-terminal DNA-binding domain constrains the subunits of the AraC dimer in an orientation that makes it energetically favorable to bind to distal ( O2 and I1 ) rather than adjacent ( I1 and I2 ) targets ( 11 , 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>As described more fully in the accompanying paper ( Saviola et al. , 1998 ) , we now favor a mechanism for AraC action in which the N-terminal arm of AraC binds to the DNA-binding domain of the protein in the absence of arabinose , and is pulled away from the domain in the presence of arabinose , thereby providing more freedom to the DNA-binding domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>While the N-terminal arm binds to arabinose in the liganded protein , the absence of arabinose frees the N-terminal arm of AraC to bind to the DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>In AraC , the additional domain dimerizes the protein3 ,4 , contains a binding site for arabinose , and possesses an N-terminal arm that plays a key role in controlling the arabinose-dependent DNA-binding properties of the protein5 ,6 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>Schleif and coworkers have found that , in the absence of arabinose , this N-terminal arm switches to interacting with the AraC DNA-binding domain ( 9 , 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>For AraC in the absence of ligand , the N-terminal arm constrains the DNA-binding C-terminal domain ( 23 , 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The common ligand-binding domains that are fused to DNA-binding domains in bacteria are : ( 1 ) the double-stranded L-helix , for example in AraC [ 2,3 ] ; ( 2 ) the PAS domain found in various FAD-binding transcription factors such as white collar 1 and 2 from Neurospora [ 4,5 ] ; ( 3 ) ACT , and related ligand-binding domains with an identical fold [ 6 ] ; ( 4 ) the solute-binding domains [ 3 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12757941" target="_blank">12757941</a>]<br></li>
<li>Some members of the DSBH superfamily function as ligand-binding domains fused to HTH domains , for example in the transcription factor AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12757941" target="_blank">12757941</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because AraC can bind to two half-sites in direct or inverted repeat orientation , or when the halfsites have been separated by an additional ten base-pairs ( Carra & Schleif , 1993 ) , attractive mechanisms for AraC action include free rotation of the protein 's two DNA-binding domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results do not support the possibility mentioned above that the poor solubility of AraC results from unfolded DNA-binding domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , the putative DNA-binding domains of AraC and Tn3 repressors do not contain Gly at position 11 either , but cysteine and serine , respectively ( 28-29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3515317" target="_blank">3515317</a>]<br></li>
<li>The construction of such functional chimeras demonstrates that AraC possesses a modular structure , with independent domains capable of dimerizing and of binding to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results from both fusion experiments indicate that AraC contains separate dimerization and DNA-binding domains and locate these domains within the sequence of protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The genetic and physical studies referred to above leave little doubt that the N-terminal arms of AraC play a central and critical role in the protein 's response to arabinose through their influence on the protein 's DNA-binding domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION The N-terminal arms of the AraC protein play a key role in communicating the status of arabinose binding by the dimerization domains to the DNA-binding domains ( see for reviews ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>These chimeras functioned well in vivo and in vitro , and here we show that AraC contains functional domains for dimerization , arabinose binding , DNA-binding , and activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The experiments were designed to locate dimerization and DNA-binding domains , and it that these expected chimeric was not same proteins would also allow localization of the transcriptionactivation and arabinose-binding portions of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the minus arabinose repressing state , left , the AraC DNA-binding domains are held in a position that favors looping by binding to the two widely separated DNA half-sites araO2 and araI1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19422057" target="_blank">19422057</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , the arms bind more tightly over the sugar , freeing the DNA-binding domains to bind to the araI1 and araI2 half-sites , from which position AraC stimulates activity of the pBAD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>An alternate model has been proposed ( 17 ) in which the N-terminal arm of AraC , which is freed in the absence of arabinose , contacts the DNA-binding domains and constrains them in a way that promotes binding to widely separated sites and DNA looping .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Apparently , the two DNA-binding domains of the dimeric AraC protein are held such that the protein prefers to engage in DNA looping interactions in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>As discussed below , these results indicate that the orientations of the DNA-binding domains of AraC are constrained in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , genetic , physiological , and physical experiments suggest or are consistent with the arms binding to the DNA-binding domains 1 -- 3,7,8 of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>Notwithstanding the results in this paper showing that the N-terminal half of AraC can participate in specific dimer formation , results do not eliminate the possibility that in our vivo the DNA-binding domains themselves of both AraC and LexA are unstable and are stabilized , but not dimerized , by additional protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding of of the DNA-binding domains of AraC to arabinose to AraC causes the protein to contact nonadjacent DNA half-sites , cease DNA looping and favor binding to probably by reducing the distance that the the adjacent I1 and I2 half-sites ( 4 , 6 ) , DNA-binding domains can be separated resulting in activation of transcription from ( 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>A central question is how arabinose modulates the DNA-binding activity of AraC , converting it from a protein dimer that loops DNA to one that favors binding to closely spaced sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>To assess possible CAP-AraC interactions in vivo , we compared the amount of AraC binding in the presence and absence of CAP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is particularly important for AraC binding upstream of ydeN , since this interaction appears to be completely dependent upon arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>A similar situation is found with AraC , where the dimerisation motif was located in its N-terminal region ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>In fact , mutations at the unconserved N-terminal region in the XylS ( 23 , 36 ) and AraC ( 7 ) regulators led to an alteration in effector speciﬁcity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with this , Bustos and Schleif ( 3 ) showed that the isolated AraC C terminal is competent for this activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The key to this mechanism is a small group of residues at the very N-terminal end of AraC known as the `` Nterminal arm '' .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>RhaR T279 aligns with AraC R251 , which has been proposed to interact with residues in the N-terminal arm of AraC ( Wu and Schleif , 2001b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the structure of AraC determined in the absence of arabinose ( 14 ) , the overall features of the protein are similar except that the lack of bound sugar leads to a disordering of 12 N-terminal arm residues ( residues 7-18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the AraC mechanism , the very N-terminal residues ( the arm ) of AraC bind to the CTD in the absence of arabinose to prevent transcription-activation and cause formation of a DNA loop .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>This model is supported by genetic analyses , notably , mutations that alter amino acids in the AraC N-terminal arm that result in AraC-dependent activation of paraBAD in the absence of arabinose ( 19 , 21 , 22 , 34 , 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Supporting this model is the observation that deletions and point mutations in the N-terminal arm that include residues 7-15 result in arabinose-independent activation of pBAD by AraC ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with the arm inhibiting activity in the absence of effector , N-terminal deletions of seven to 20 residues ( within the arm ) led to increased basal activation by AraC ( were constitutive ) ( Saviola et al. , 1998 ; Soisson et al. , 1997b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike AraC , Nterminal truncations suggested that RhaS and RhaR do n't use an N-terminal arm to inhibit activity in the absence of effector .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>If residues at the very N-terminus of RhaS or RhaR performed functions similar to the AraC Nterminal arm , then one or more N-terminal truncations would be predicted to result in activation of transcription in the absence of L-rhamnose to higher basal levels than wild-type RhaS or RhaR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>The corresponding AraC sequence within this conserved domain is shown at the bottom of the ﬁgure , where the ﬁrst amino acid residue corresponds to Arg 180 and the last residue corresponds to Gly 279 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The region of greatest amino acid sequence homology identiﬁed in XylS/AraC members is clearly a set of 99 residues found in most of the proteins at the C-terminal end of the regulators , although in some cases it is at the N-terminal end ( CafR and Rob from E. coli ) or in the central domain ( Ada from E. coli and S. typhimurium and Ybbb from B. subtilis ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal region of MaoB ( amino acid residues 182 to 217 ) was 46.9 % identical over 32 amino acids to AraC of E. coli and 30.8 % identical over 39 amino acids to MelR of E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results also showed that His6-RhaS-CTD and His6-RhaR-CTD did not respond to Lrhamnose availability ( data not shown ) , which was expected since , based on sequence similarity with AraC , L-rhamnose binding is predicted to be a function of the RhaS and RhaR N-terminal domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>This region of s is located in the C-terminal 70 domain ( CTD ; amino acids 590 ± 613 ) , which also contains residues required for transcription-activation by Ada ( Landini and Busby , 1999 ) , lcI ( Kuldell and Hochschild , 1994 ; Li et al. , 1994 ) , AraC ( Hu and Gross , 1985 ) , RhaS ( Bhende and Egan , 2000 ) and the cyclic AMP receptor protein ( CRP ) ( Lonetto et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11115116" target="_blank">11115116</a>]<br></li>
<li>We were also not surprised to ﬁnd that RhaS-CTD was capable of equivalent transcription-activation in the absence and the presence of L-rhamnose ( data not shown ) , since amino acid sequence alignment with AraC suggests that the RhaS N-terminal domain likely binds L-rhamnose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">AraC evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>Some of the largest such families ( Perez-Rueda et al. 2004 ) are the LysR ( Henikoff et al. 1988 ) , TetR ( Ramos et al. 2005 ) , IclR ( Nasser et al. 1994 ) , GntR ( Haydon and Guest 1991 ) , and AraC ( Gallegos et al. 1997 ) superfamilies .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16672238" target="_blank">16672238</a>]<br></li>
<li>A search of the BLOCKS database to reveal more distant relationships identified the first 53 residues of ModE to be similar to both the AraC and LysR families of regulatory proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9210473" target="_blank">9210473</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , five gene products of unknown function ( ycgE , ydeO , yhiW , yhiX and yjhI ) were predicted to encode regulatory proteins belonging to the AraC , IclR and MerR families ( Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11298273" target="_blank">11298273</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of these families have the opposite modes of action : RbsR is a classical repressor whose true inducer is D-ribose , whereas AraC and XylR are primarily activators of transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11750821" target="_blank">11750821</a>]<br></li>
