<li>At the rhaBAD promoter , which is regulated by an AraC family member , RhaR binds immediately adjacent to RNA polymerase and CAP binds upstream from RhaR ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Escherichia coli AraC is the founding member of a large family of transcription factors ( TFs ) found across a wide range of bacterial species ( 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our studies , we have focussed attention on the E. coli MelR protein , which is a member of the AraC family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is a member of the AraC family of transcription activators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is a member of the AraC family of transcription factors and binds to 18-base pair target sequences ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>This means that each site provides sufficient nucle-otides to guarantee the binding of both HTH motifs belonging to the C-terminal domain of each subunit in the functional dimer , as reported for other members of the AraC/XylS family such as AdpA , AraC , MelR and XylS ( Reeder and Schleif , 1993 ; Gonzalez-Perez et al. , 1999 ; Grainger et al. , 2003 ; Yamazaki et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC is the founder member of a large family of gene regulatory proteins , the AraC family ; the activities of many members of this family are regulated by small ligands ( reviewed by Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusions All members of the AraC family of bacterial transcription factors contain two putative HTH motifs ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 7A shows the amino acid sequences of the likely recognition helices of the HTH motifs of MelR and other AraC family members , aligned according to Gallegos et al. ( 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The amino acid sequences of the putative recognition helices for different AraC family members aligned as in Gallegos et al. ( 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We then analyzed and compared changes in the protein synthesis profile between the rob mutant ( MK107 ) and its parental strain ( MC4100 ) , since Rob appears to be a member of the AraC transcriptional regulator family ( Skarstad et al. 1993 , and see below ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7476863" target="_blank">7476863</a>]<br></li>
<li>As far as we are aware , this is the first report of a direct interaction between CRP and an AraC family member ( although there may be a parallel with the interaction between CRP and CaiF reported by Buchet et al. , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Whereas PaaX is a member of the GntR family of regulators , PaaR is usually a TetR-like repressor ( Hamlin et al. , 2009 ) , although a PaaR regulator of the AraC family has been also proposed in Rhodococcus jostii RHA1 ( Navarro-Llorens et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24983528" target="_blank">24983528</a>]<br></li>
<li>The YhiX protein appears to be a member of the AraC family of regulators and was indirectly implicated as a gad regulator in gene array studies ( Tao et al. , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11238978" target="_blank">11238978</a>]<br></li>
<li>This occurs typically by MarA ( Okusu et al. , 1996 ; Barbosa and Levy , 2000 ) and SoxS ( Ma et al. , 1996 ; White et al. , 1997 ) , both belonging to the XylS/AraC family of transcription regulators ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12791142" target="_blank">12791142</a>]<br></li>
<li>Most of the regulatory proteins of the XylS/AraC family have a similarly large size , except those rare exceptions such as MarA and SoxS ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12791142" target="_blank">12791142</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recently Rhee et al. ( 30 ) determined the crystal structure of the ﬁrst AraC family member , MarA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequence homology within the AraC family suggests that the MarA fold is structurally conserved ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Rhee et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Third , MarA , SoxS and Rob belong to a subfamily of the AraC family of DNA-binding proteins ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10564485" target="_blank">10564485</a>]<br></li>
<li>The conserved DNA-binding domains of other AraC family members are expected to adopt the same tertiary structure as MarA , since they share greater than 20 % similarity ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>The proximal ChbR site overlaps the -35 region of the chbB promoter and is thus well positioned to behave like a Class II activator protein as do other members of the AraC family ( Egan et al. , 2000 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>The SoxS protein , a 13-kD member of the AraC family , stimulates the transcription of multiple genes through binding to their promoter regions and interaction with RNA polymerase ( Li and Demple 1994 , 1996 ; Jair et al. 1996 ; Martin et al. 1999 , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18368388" target="_blank">18368388</a>]<br></li>
<li>The consensus sequence of the AraC binding site is not yet clearly deﬁned ; however , the consensus binding sequence for SoxS , another member of AraC family , is well characterized ( 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20543070" target="_blank">20543070</a>]<br></li>
<li>No such motif was detected in thefHmC promoter region , but there are regions of partial dyad symmetry which might provide more appropriate binding sites for a member of the AraC family of regulators , such as SoxS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8000525" target="_blank">8000525</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mol Plant Microbe Interact 13:1243 -- 1250 Munson G , Holcomb LG , Scott JR ( 2001 ) Novel group of virulence activators within the AraC family that are not restricted to upstream binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21559929" target="_blank">21559929</a>]<br></li>
<li>Novel group of virulence activators within the AraC family that are not restricted to upstream binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17189357" target="_blank">17189357</a>]<br></li>
<li>If the OmpR and AraC families were related to the LysR family , then helix-turn-helix predictions would be expected near the amino termini .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3413113" target="_blank">3413113</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in each case , helix-turn-helix predictions are made for stretches found near the middle of each OmpR and AraC family protein ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3413113" target="_blank">3413113</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the amino acid sequence of MaoB showed a high level of homology with respect to the helix-turn-helix motif of the AraC family in its C-terminus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal domain of the AraC family has a helix-turn-helix motif and a high degree of sequence homology , where the consensus sequence of a characteristic conserved motif is I-DIA -- GF-S -- YF -- F -- G-TPS -- R ( 5 , 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>The nature of the interactions between the transcription activator and RNAP depends on the position and orientation of the DNA-bound activator with respect to the location of the − 35 promoter hexamer .8 Thus , at class I promoters , the activator binding site lies upstream of the − 35 element , and the predominant interaction of the activator is with the `` 287 '' determinant of the C-terminal domain ( CTD ) of the α subunit of RNAP .9 On the other hand , at class II promoters , the activator binding site partially or completely overlaps the − 35 element such that the DNA-bound activator is able to interact directly with region 4 of the σ70 subunit ( σ70 R4 ) .10 -15 Rob , SoxS , MarA , and TetD form a highly paralogous subset of proteins16 within the AraC / XylS family of transcriptional activators , whose hallmark is the presence of two helix -- turn -- helix ( HTH ) DNA binding motifs per monomer .17 Extensive amino acid sequence identity is shared between Rob ( 55 % ) , MarA ( 42 % ) , and TetD ( 49 % ) over the l07-amino-acid length of SoxS , the shortest member of the subset .16 Accordingly , the paralogs share many characteristics .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22465792" target="_blank">22465792</a>]<br></li>
<li>The other domain of AraC/XylS proteins ( usually the N-terminal domain , NTD ) is not conserved throughout the family ; however , proteins that also share sequence similarity with AraC in this domain make up the largest subset of the family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC/XylS family consists of more than 130 proteins that are identiﬁed by a 99-amino-acid region of sequence similarity within the DNA-binding domain of AraC ( 17 , 18 , 44 , 53 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>The proteins in Group 2 belong to the XylS/AraC family ( Tobin & Schleif , 1990 ) and carry the helix-turn-helix motif in the region about one-third from the C-terminal ( Gallegos et al. , 1993 ) , although the upstream region is missing in SoxS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8729576" target="_blank">8729576</a>]<br></li>
<li>A consensus sequence has been found in the C-terminus in a comparison of 27 members of the XylS/AraC family of regulators ( Gallegos e t al. , 1993 ) which is rich in a-helix and could be involved in DNA binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8704970" target="_blank">8704970</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC family of gene regulators are DNA-binding proteins that contain probable helix-turn-helix DNA recognition sequences ; such a sequence is also present in SoxS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1653416" target="_blank">1653416</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Rob amino acid sequence , deduced from the DNA sequence of the cloned rob gene , revealed it as the fourth member of a subset of highly related proteins within the XylS/AraC subfamily of DNA binding proteins that have the signature of a putative helix-turn-helix motif ( 11 , 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>]<br></li>
<li>The size of this binding site , which may actually be less than 21 bp ( 9 ) , is similar to that of the ; 17-bp sequence bound by a monomer of AraC protein ( 7 ) , a founder of the XylS/AraC subfamily of DNA binding proteins to which Rob , SoxS , and MarA belong ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>]<br></li>
<li>© 2002 Oxford University Press DNA binding of the transcription activator protein MelR from Escherichia coli and its C-terminal domain Victoria J. Howard , Tamara A. Belyaeva , Stephen J. W. Busby and Eva I. Hyde * School of Biosciences , The University of Birmingham , Edgbaston , Birmingham B15 2TT , UK Received December 30 , 2001 ; Revised March 11 , 2002 ; Accepted April 19 , 2002 ABSTRACT MelR is an Escherichia coli transcription factor belonging to the AraC family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>SoxS has a potential DNA-binding domain ( helix-turn-helix motif ) and is a member of the XylS/AraC family of positive transcriptional regulatory proteins ( Wu and Weiss , 1991 ; Amabile-Cuevas and Demple , 1991 ; Gallegos etai , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7891555" target="_blank">7891555</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , there is C-terminal region of high homology between MaoB and other proteins such as the region of the so-called helix-turn-helix DNA binding motif of the AraC family which is present in regulatory proteins ( 5 , 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>All members of the AraC family contain two helix -- turn -- helix ( HTH ) motifs that contact two segments of the DNA major groove at target sites on the same DNA face .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>A similarity of XylR protein to other AraC family proteins whose DNA-binding motifs are organized as two helix-turn-helix ( HTH ) structures lies in the COOH-terminal portion of the peptide as for other proteins in the group ( 9 , 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9371449" target="_blank">9371449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Many AraC family proteins consist of ª 300 amino acids : the N-terminal ª 200 amino acids constitute a ligand-sensing domain , whereas the C-terminal ª 100 amino acids constitute a DNA-binding domain , predicted to contain two helix -- turn -- helix ( HTH ) DNA-binding motifs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>This strongly suggests that the surface of the DNA-binding HTH , located towards the C-terminal end of AraC family members ( HTH 2 ) , has evolved to contact s , and this may explain why so many AraC family members bind to sites that overlap the -35 elements at their target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The signiﬁcant homology between the C-terminal domain of MaoB and other members in the AraC family suggests that the C-terminal domain of MaoB binds to speciﬁc DNA to activate the maoA transcription , and the nonhomologous NH2-terminal or central region of MaoB may recognize a chemical signal , tyramine , or a compound regulated by tyramine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>Many members of the AraC family also contain an 170-amino-acid ligand-binding domain which regulates their activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In particular , amino acid sequence similarities argue that MelR residues 25 to 100 constitute a ligand-binding cupin fold ( 5 , 6 ) and MelR residues 190 to 302 fold as an AraC family DNA-binding domain ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of the AraC family typically contain two domains : a non-conserved region which binds effector molecules ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ) and a conserved domain of approximately 100 amino acid residues which binds DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like many other members of the AraC family , MelR appears to consist of two domains : a < 100 amino acid C-terminal DNA-binding domain and a < 200 amino acids N-terminal melibiose-sensing domain ( MichaÂn et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In members of the LysR family the DNA-binding domain is N-terminal and the signal-recognition domain C-ter-minal , while the converse is true for members of the AraC family ( Gallegos et al. , 1993 ; Schell , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9210473" target="_blank">9210473</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mechanism of RclR Activation -- Based on RclR homology to regulators of the AraC family ( 43 ) , RclR is predicted to be a two-domain protein with an N-terminal domain presumed to be involved in sensing ( residues 1 -- 162 ) and a C-terminal DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24078635" target="_blank">24078635</a>]<br></li>
<li>Substitution for residues comprising the hydrophobic core of MarA The homology among the AraC family of proteins is greatest for residues which comprise the hydrophobic core of the DNA-binding motifs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>This DNA-binding domain has also been shown to be involved in transcription activation in a number of AraC/XylS family proteins including Ada , RhaS , AraC , MelR , MarA , SoxS , XylS , and UreR ( 1 , 4 , 5 , 15 , 16 , 20 -- 22 , 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>]<br></li>
<li>SoxS protein is a member of the XylS/AraC family , sharing the conserved DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10102373" target="_blank">10102373</a>]<br></li>
<li>There are currently structures available for the DNA-binding domain of two AraC / XylS family proteins , MarA and Rob ( 31 , 46 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>Wickstrum , J.R. , Skredenske , J.M. , Kolin , A. , Jin , D.J. , Fang , J. and Egan , S.M. ( 2007 ) Transcription activation by the DNA-binding domain of the AraC family protein RhaS in the absence of its effector-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21398637" target="_blank">21398637</a>]<br></li>
<li>This carboxyl-terminal segment is implicated in DNA binding and may be sufﬁcient for transcriptional activation in some members of the XylS-AraC family ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7896685" target="_blank">7896685</a>]<br></li>
