<li>A possible explanation for the differences among sites is thatataraFGland - FG2 , the specific sequences that interact with AraC are evenly distributed , with some mismatches allowed in each of four turns of the DNAhelix .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>MATERIALS AND METHODS General Procedures , Plasmids , and Strains Plasmid pWR03 , derived from pSE380 , contains the 7 full-length AraC sequence , nucleotides 1 -- 876 , between the NcoI and SacI sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>8 7,12,13 Plasmid AraCTF was derived from pET21b by cloning 14 nucleotides 1 -- 546 of AraC between the NdeI and AdeI sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , in contrast to the sequences recognized by other activators such as CAP , AraC or CI protein ( de Crombrugge et al. , 1984 ; Hendrickson and Schleif , 1985 ; Pabo and Lewis , 1982 ) the MalT-dependent promoters do not contain two-fold symmetrical elements , but possess a conserved hexanucleotide sequence which is present in one or three copies in either orientation , depending on the promoter ( Chapon and Raibaud , 1985 ; Raibaud et al. , 1985 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3015733" target="_blank">3015733</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two mutant AraC proteins were isolated that no longer respond to the loss or the methylation of guanines in a pattern that is consistent with a directly repeated recognition sequence , and the pattern is inconsistent with an inverted-repeat .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sequence similarity with AraC suggested that the ﬁrst contacting motif of RhaS was a helix-turn-helix .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>Methylation and ethylation interference assays show that AraC protein binds along one side of the DNA to four adjacentmajor grooveregions at each of the araFG1 and aruFG2 sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data suggest strongly that AraC protein is oriented on one side of the DNA double helix and binds to the DNA throughinteractions with specific bases in four adjacent major groove regions.Compared with the AraC contacts to the araBAD araI site , the FG1 and FG2 sites share highly conserved guanine contacts along three turns of the helix ( 2 3of Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , AraC likely binds with similar DNA sequence speciﬁcity across all Enterobacteriaceae species .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previously , it was suggested that AraC binds at araIBAoto a sequence with 2-fold symmetry spanning three turns of the DNA helix ( 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been suggested that AraC binds at araIsao to a sequence with 2-fold symmetry spanning three turns of the DNA helix ( Hendrickson & Schleif , 1985 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>Brunelle and Schleif ( 26 ) , using genetic and chemical analysis , obtained data that strongly support the model that AraC protein bindsvia an H-T-H region to a directly repeated sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The chemical interference and genetic data , combined with the consensus sequence for AraC proteinbinding to ura promoters , support abinding motif in which two directly repeated units each span two adjacent turns of the DNA helix .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results show that AraC protein is located on one side of four adjacent , helical-turn regions of the DNA , and the datasupport the proposal that each AraC monomer binds to two turns of the DNA helix to a directly repeated DNA sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lastly , there is a clustering of A or T residues near the center of the consensus sequence , suggesting that the regions of DNA comprising the minor grooves that face AraC may be especially susceptible to conformational distortion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>The location of one of these regions is precisely aligned with the ChIP-seq peak , suggesting that this sequence is bound by AraC under the conditions tested .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Asp256 of AraC has also been shown to be important for DNA sequence rec-ognition and was predicted to be a part of a second H-T-H motif ( H-T-H 2 ) ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal domain of the AraC family has a helix-turn-helix motif and a high degree of sequence homology , where the consensus sequence of a characteristic conserved motif is I-DIA -- GF-S -- YF -- F -- G-TPS -- R ( 5 , 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with the information content of the motif derived from the E. coli AraC ChIP-chip data and with the known consensus sequence ( Fig. 1B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding site recognition by Rns , a virulence regulator in the AraC family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17189357" target="_blank">17189357</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10873449" target="_blank">10873449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , we found that I1 consists of two separate regions in which speciﬁc contacts to AraC occur .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sequences surrounding AraC binding sites upstream of E. coli araB , araF , araE , araJ , and ytfQ and within dcp ( 30 bp upstream sequence and 30 bp downstream sequence in addition to the 19-mer AraC site ) were individually aligned with equivalent regions ( i.e. , the sequence 500 bp upstream of the homologous gene , or for the site within E. coli dcp , the entire homologous gene ; for S. enterica araT , sequence was taken from 500 to 100 with respect to the gene start , since these genes may be misannotated ) from S. enterica , Citrobacter rodentium ICC168 , Enterobacter sp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine whether regulation of AraC target genes is conserved across the family Enterobacteria-ceae , we aligned sequence surrounding E. coli and/or S. enterica AraC sites identiﬁed in this work with equivalent regions from four other Enterobacteriaceae species ( Citrobacter rodentium , Enterobacter sp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is likely that XylR binds as a dimeric form , each molecule occupying two helical turns of each half site as in AraC ( 2 , 23 ) or as in other helix-turn-helix proteins ( 1 ) such as cI ( 16 ) and Cro ( 49 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9371449" target="_blank">9371449</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC directly binds the PxylA promoter region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose binds to AraC in a pocket located within a â-barrel ( Figure 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10995226" target="_blank">10995226</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon induction by L-arabinose , one subunit of AraC releases the distal O2 site and instead binds to the adjacent promoter-proximal site I2 , thereby activating transcription from PBAD ( Lee et al. , 1987 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon induction of arabinose , AraC releases the upstream araO2 half-site and binds to the downstream araI1-araI2 site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>This was revealed by direct in vivo footprinting measurements in which the I2 half-site at pBAD was converted to the O2 sequence , and thus AraC had the opportunity to loop between I1 and either the distal O2 half-site or bind I1 and the adjacent half-site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , arabinose converts AraC from a form that binds to distal targets ( O2 and I1 ) to a form that binds to adjacent targets ( I1 and I2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC dimer binds the operator sequence I1-I2 tightly in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>MarA is an AraC family global regulator ( Rhee et al. , 1998 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ) , which transcriptionally activates at least 21 promoters , the marA regulon ( Barbosa and Levy , 2000 ; Pomposiello et al. , 2001 ; Martin and Rosner , 2002 ; 2003 ) , by binding to a site ( marbox ) overlapping or upstream of the -35 signal ( Martin et al. , 1996 ; 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15225313" target="_blank">15225313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , we split each binding site into two ; each half-site ( shown in Fig. 11A ) was of sufficient length ( 21 bp ) to allow the binding of the two HTH motifs present in the C-terminal domain of a GadX ( or GadW ) monomer , as in the case of the AraC / XylS-like proteins ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Egan , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Introduction Most members of the AraC family of bacterial gene regulatory proteins are transcription activators that bind to speciﬁc 18 -- 20 bp sequences at target promoters : in many cases , activity is regulated by the binding of a small ligand ( reviewed by Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Martin and Rosner , 2001 ; Egan , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC Protein Contacts Asymmetric Sites in the Escherichia coli araFGH Promoter * AraC protein regulates the transcription of arabinose transport and catabolic operons in Escherichia coli through interaction with specific DNA sequences in the promoter regions of the operons .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two regions upstream of araT have sequences similar to the AraC consensus motif .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in comparison to AraC protein , the basis for speciﬁc binding of Rob and SoxS is unclear , especially since a consensus of target sequences is difﬁcult to discern ( 10 , 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>]<br></li>
<li>This mode of binding to DNA is consistent with biochemical studies of Rob 's interactions with various promoter sequences and with chemical footprinting studies of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10802742" target="_blank">10802742</a>]<br></li>
<li>I1-I2 vs I1-I2 I1-I1 vs I1-O2 I1-O2 vs I1-I2 I1-I2 vs I1-ns 170 10 18 4 6 5 2 1 70 3 20 10 10 0.5 10 5 AraC possesses an intrinsic DNA - looping preference We also tested whether AraC possesses an intrinsic preference to loop between distally located half-sites rather than bind to adjacent halfsites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , we demonstrated that AraC possesses an intrinsic preference to loop between distally located half-sites rather than bind adjacently located half-sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC binds to two half-sites within rrrrrl ( Lee rf al. .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848302" target="_blank">1848302</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since AraC binds araI and araFG2 with equal stoichiometry , we conclude that a dimer binds the araFG sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>They have proposed that the DNA loop formed in the presence of L-arabinose involves AraC bound to the araOl and araO2 sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA loop models propose that in the absence of L-arabinose a loop is formed between AraC bound at the araI site and the araO2 site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , a ﬂexible inter-domain linker allows AraC to bind adjacent , tandem sites when arabinose frees the DNA-binding domains of AraC from the constraints imposed by the 2-fold symmetry dimer core formed by the dimerization domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15491603" target="_blank">15491603</a>]<br></li>
<li>When arabinose is absent , the AraC dimer prefers binding to half-sites separated by a long stretch of DNA ( V200 bp ) , thus forming a DNA loop .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11750821" target="_blank">11750821</a>]<br></li>
<li>On addition of arabinose , AraC tends to bind adjacent half-sites with a spacer of 4 bp [ 10 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11750821" target="_blank">11750821</a>]<br></li>
<li>Dimerization occurs between adjacent DNA sites when AraC binds arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , transcription of the araC gene is repressed by two AraC molecules that bind to two DNA sites ( O2 and I1 ) that ﬂank the araC promoter and are separated by 210 bp ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION At the E. coli arabinose operon regulatory region , transcription is repressed by the binding of two AraC molecules at two targets that are in the same orientation and separated by 210 bp , and a repression loop forms ( 4,5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , the a , raBAD operon is repressed by AraC protein bound at two sites whose centers are separated by 211 bp ( Dunn et al. , 1984 ; Hahn et al. , 1984 ; Lee & Schleif , 1989 ; Martin et at .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC , one of the members in Group 2 , is suggested to bind to at least two sites around the promoter region and to form a double stranded DNA loop of more than 200 bp in the absence of arabinose , cAMP or CRP , while the loop could open in the presence of both arabinose and cAMP-CRP ( Dunn et al. , 1984 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8729576" target="_blank">8729576</a>]<br></li>
<li>Amino Acid-DNA Contacts by RhaS : an AraC Family Transcription Activator PRASANNA M. BHENDE AND SUSAN M. EGAN * Department of Molecular Biosciences , University of Kansas , Lawrence , Kansas 66045 Received 17 March 1999/Accepted 15 June 1999 RhaS , an AraC family protein , activates rhaBAD transcription by binding to rhaI , a site consisting of two 17-bp inverted-repeat half-sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike the binding sites of many transcription factors , the two half-sites of the known AraC binding sequences are in direct repeat orientation rather than inverted-repeat orientation ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because AraC can bind to two half-sites in direct or inverted-repeat orientation , or when the halfsites have been separated by an additional ten base-pairs ( Carra & Schleif , 1993 ) , attractive mechanisms for AraC action include free rotation of the protein 's two DNA binding domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the dimeric regulatory protein of the L-arabinose operon in Escherichia coli , AraC , can bind to two half-sites in a direct repeat orientation or to two half-sites in inverted-repeat orientation ( 13 ) , each monomer of the protein is likely to possess significant flexibility and could well consist of a dimerization domain loosely connected to a DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8516313" target="_blank">8516313</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding AraC protein at araI and at araO2 , sites separated by 211 bp , and association of these two proteins to form a DNA loop is necessary for the negative regulation or repression of the araBAD promoter PBAD ( 1-4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2643114" target="_blank">2643114</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recently , it has been shown that repression of gal requires two gal repressor binding sites separated by about 110 bp ( 34-35 ) and also two targets for AraC are required for maximal repression of the araBAD promoter Table 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2994018" target="_blank">2994018</a>]<br></li>
<li>Even the small-spacing candidates with separations between araO2 and aral of 34 , 33 , and 32 bp , which leave just the two AraC protein binding sites intact , remained repression-positive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2643114" target="_blank">2643114</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is generally agreed that the 17 bp long AraC binding site has to be recognised by at least two protein motifs , as it encompasses two consecutive major grooves that are contacted by the protein ( Hendrickson & Schleif , 1985 ; Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ; Lu et al. , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The protection of two 19 bp direct repeats , separated by 4 bp , by the ChbR protein is consistent with an AraC type binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutational studies of the DNA-binding site of AraC ( 33 ) showed that two groups of bases , 8 bp apart , termed the A and the B boxes , are important for protein binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Also , we were puzzled that the binding sites for MelR at the melAB promoter were located further upstream than binding sites for other AraC family members at their target promoters ( Keen et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , with AraC at the araBAD promoter , a combination of genetics and biochemistry has shown that the binding orientation is such that the C-terminally located HTH motif is adjacent to the promoter -35 element ( Niland et al. , 1996 ) , and that , during activation , AraC binds to two adjacent sites as a direct repeat ( Reeder and Schleif , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The separation of phosphate contacts across a major groove region for the AraC sites varies from 3 to 6 bp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N-terminus and central region of the proteins in the XylS/AraC family are thought to include a region which recognizes chemical signals and contains binding sites for activator molecules that confer specificity ( Ramos e t a / .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8704970" target="_blank">8704970</a>]<br></li>
<li>To conﬁrm that this motif matched the AraC consensus binding sequence , we used the TOMTOM program ( 17 ) to search RegTransBase ( 22 ) , a curated database of bacterial transcription factor binding sites , and found that the top hit indeed matched the AraC consensus sequence ( P 10 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this work , we use a combination of ChIP-chip and transcription proﬁling with microarrays to identify all binding sites and all direct regulatory targets of E. coli AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We also identify all binding sites and all direct regulatory targets of AraC in the related species Salmonella enterica using a combination of ChIP-seq and RNA-seq .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In gels ( a ) and ( c ) the indicated targets contain two binding sites in tandem repeat , in order to increase binding to an AraC dimer by cooperativity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>We conclude that , although the sequences of the binding sites differ among ara promoters , it is likely that AraC uses the same binding motif .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>These mutationsare at positions that arenot conserved among the AraC binding sites orat positions at which araFGl fails to conform to the consensus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC sites in araE excluded .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1943993" target="_blank">1943993</a>]<br></li>
<li>ChIP-chip identiﬁes noncanonical AraC binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Candidate binding sites for RbsR and AraC were detected .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11750821" target="_blank">11750821</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genome-wide mapping of AraC binding sites in S. enterica .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>A directly repeated sequence spanning four turns of the helix also is evident when AraC binding sites are compared ( Lee et al. , 1987 ; Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>In every case except araO2 , the sequence protected by AraC can be divided into two consensus sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>The importance of using experimental data from multiple species is especially high for TFs that have degenerate binding motifs , such as AraC , since binding sites can not easily be predicted from DNA sequence alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>A consensus sequence for AraC binding was obtained by comparing the sites from E. coli and S. typhimurium ara promoters ( 28 , 108 -- 110 , 158 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The consensus sequence developed by comparing the seven AraC binding sites of the E. coli and S. typhimuriurn ara promoters ( 26-28 ) and the datapresented here show that the predominant similarity among the sites is a directly repeated sequence ( Fig. 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , RhaS H-T-H 1 contacts the inner major grooves of the rhaI inverted-repeat site ( Fig. 4 ) , consistent with the expectation that the promoter proximal monomers of RhaS and AraC bind in the same relative orientation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>The end of the downstream putative AraC site is only 21 bp from the annotated gene start for araT , a distance inconsistent with activation of araTU transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>translation start site of araT is likely to be incorrectly annotated , and the downstream putative AraC site is likely to be located upstream of position 40 with respect to the araTU transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of L-rhamnose , the AraC family activator RhaS ( reviewed in reference 12 ) binds to a site that spans from position 232 to position 281 relative to the rhaBAD transcription start site ( 9 , 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10852886" target="_blank">10852886</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the shorter fragment , from 371 to 1 , showed no repression by AraC , suggesting association of AraC with the sequence around the transcription start site ( Fig .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our reporter fusions indicate that maximal repression by AraC requires sequence between 1 and 15 relative to the transcription start site ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>( C ) ChIP of FLAG-tagged AraC coupled with quantitative real-time PCR to measure binding upstream of ytfQ in a wild-type strain ( AMD187 ) or a strain with a mutation in the putative AraC binding site ( JTW010 ) for cells grown in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
