<li>This observation is interesting in light of the fact that the AraC protein appears to recognize a DNA-binding site that contains a direct repeat structure ( Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ) , while the RhaR protein recognizes an inverted-repeat binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2405166" target="_blank">2405166</a>]<br></li>
<li>The number of matches to each position of each AraC site was determined , and the fraction of all species with a match to the reference sequence at each position was calculated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The size of this binding site , which may actually be less than 21 bp ( 9 ) , is similar to that of the ; 17-bp sequence bound by a monomer of AraC protein ( 7 ) , a founder of the XylS/AraC subfamily of DNA binding proteins to which Rob , SoxS , and MarA belong ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>]<br></li>
<li>The more upstream conserved sequence that resembles an AraC binding site falls outside the region predicted by the ChIP-seq data ; hence , it may bind AraC under other growth conditions , e.g. , in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The strong down mutations are at highly conserved positions that match the consensus AraC binding site ( Fig. 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The putative AraC binding site , as determined through sequence analysis , is boxed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>The consensus sequence of the AraC binding site is not yet clearly deﬁned ; however , the consensus binding sequence for SoxS , another member of AraC family , is well characterized ( 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20543070" target="_blank">20543070</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA contacts lost by two mutants were clearly in a pattern suggesting thatthe AraC binding site is a directly repeated sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding of AraC protein to this sequence , unlike the binding of CAP to its consensus sequence , is asymmetric .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequences protected by AraC protein at the araFG1 and FG2 sites also are much more consistent with the proposed directly repeated sequence than with a symmetric binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC protein binds upstream from CAP , at two different sites , one centered at position 280 and the other centered at 2154 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7768852" target="_blank">7768852</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although at pFGH AraC protein possesses two binding sites , centered at positions 279.5 and 2154.5 , placing both upstream from the CAP binding site , only the CAP-proximal site is necessary for signiﬁcant activation of transcription from pFGH ( 10 , 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>The location of the AraC binding site upstream of ytfQ is too far upstream of the transcription start site to repress transcription by directly occluding RNAP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CRP binding site is centered at position -41.5 , and two AraC binding sites , araFGl and araFG2 , are centered at positions -80 and -155 , respectively , from the transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>The MEME analysis identiﬁed a putative AraC binding site centered at positions 133.5 and 94.5 relative to the previously mapped transcription start sites of ytfQ and ppa , respectively ( Fig .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of paraBAD requires AraC to bind at adjacent 20-bp operator sites , I1 and I2 , centered at positions 63.5 and 43.5 upstream of the transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that AraC binds as a dimer to adjacent sites overlapping the transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>To identify the likely AraC binding site within the PxylA promoter , we searched the promoter regions of the xylose promoters using MEME , a motif discovery program ( 2 , 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 10 illustrates the likely organization of MelR subunits during transcription activation at the melAB promoter , with MelR binding to site 2 and site 2 cents as a direct repeat , in the same arrangement as for AraC at the ara-BAD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the addition of arabinose , AraC shifts from contacting the distal ara02 site to binding the previously unoccupied half of the aral site , breaking the DNA loop and inducing araBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8087856" target="_blank">8087856</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possibility is that AraC uses a hidden upstream binding site or nonspeciﬁc DNA and still forms a DNA loop that CAP helps to break .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>The remainder of the partially overlapping RNA polymerase binding site at pBAD was not present so as to avoid any potential cooperative interactions between AraC and RNA polymerase in the unlikely event that the change from I2 to O2 did not itself inactivate pBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of AraC protein , the transcription start of WH542 is moved upstream by 15 bp , which is consistent with polymerase binding to the new -10 sequence ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was shown that to activate transcription in ParaBAD , the AraC protein binding site must overlap the 235 region of the promoter by 4 bp ( 212 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Studies of the araBAD promoter , pBAD , show that to activate transcription the AraC protein binding site must overlap the 235 region of the promoter by 4 bp ( 25 ) ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7768852" target="_blank">7768852</a>]<br></li>
<li>One end of this loop requires AraC protein binding at the araO2 site , an operator that is located > 200 base pairs ( bp ) away from the start site of araBAD transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3041410" target="_blank">3041410</a>]<br></li>
<li>The site of AraC interaction required for activation ( araI ) is located very close to the RNA polymerase binding site ( 2-4 ) , whereas the site for repression ( araO2 ) is located at a considerable distance from the start point of araBAD transcription ( 5-8 ) ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araBAD promoter , CRP binds to a site upstream of AraC Sites I1 and I2 , and this binding is independent of the binding of AraC ( Zhang and Schleif , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , a minimal araFGH promoter consisting of the RNA polymerase binding site , the partially overlapping CAP binding site , and a binding site for AraC protein located just upstream , has been studied in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10715008" target="_blank">10715008</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araFGH promoter , CAP binds at a site adjacent to RNA polymerase and AraC binds to the upstream site ( 17 , 22 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>In any eviet natppears thatbinding to the system , the uru02 site , 200 base pairs upstream of the pro- -70 to -100 region occurs before binding at other sites and thus moter , is important for self-repression by the AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8175665" target="_blank">8175665</a>]<br></li>
<li>Small and large arrows represent AraC protein half-site sequences and RNA polymerase ( RNAP ) binding sites , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7768852" target="_blank">7768852</a>]<br></li>
<li>C At pBAD , moving of the AraC protein binding site further upstream or reversing of the orientation of the half-sites destroys the contacts and prevents induction ( 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7768852" target="_blank">7768852</a>]<br></li>
<li>We conjecture that the low occupancy results from steric hindrance in AraC protein binding by an RKA polymerase molecule bound at the pc promoter that overlaps the ara0 , site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC protein represses its own synthesis from the promoter Pc , most likely by binding to a third AraC protein binding site in the regulatory region , the operator araOl , and directly blocking RNA polymerase entry to the promoter for synthesis of AraC protein , Pc ( 8 , 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3041410" target="_blank">3041410</a>]<br></li>
