<li>Depending upon the protein , these approximately 20 bp sequences can be arranged as direct or inverted-repeats and the distance between them also varies with the protein , e.g. 4 bp for AraC but 16 or 17 for RhaS and RhaR ( Bhende and Egan , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this regard , XylR is similar to other members of the AraC family regulators that bind to direct repeat structures with a gap of 4 bp , spanning about four helical turns as a whole ( 23 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9371449" target="_blank">9371449</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , whereas AraC binds as a dimer ( 15 ) to a direct repeat of the ; 17-bp sequence ( 6 , 7 ) , Rob and SoxS bind their targets as monomers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8626315" target="_blank">8626315</a>]<br></li>
<li>Niland et al. ( 186 ) systematically substituted every base pair in a synthetic 17-bp araI1 target ( 5-TAGCATTTTTATCCA TA-39 [ the underlined bases correspond to those conserved in the consensus ] ) with each of the three possible alternatives and then used qualitative gel shift analysis to test the binding of AraC to these 51 DNA targets in the presence of L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
