<li>It is interesting to note that most of the homology between AraC , RhaS and RhaR is found in the C terminus , perhaps the two rha proteins bind their target sites using a similar sequence located in their C termini .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3316663" target="_blank">3316663</a>]<br></li>
<li>As a member of the AraC protein family , GadX is expected to bind speciﬁc sequence motifs located within or in the proximity of the target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that the araI1 sequence is not the optimal target for AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of the AraC family are deﬁned by an 110-amino-acid domain , containing two helix-turn-helix motifs , that recognizes 20-bp operator sequences at target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
