				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>Regulation of polB by AraC is particularly intriguing given the well-established function of polB in DNA replication and repair ( 52 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>araE-ygeA synteny is not well conserved , suggesting that ygeA is not a conserved AraC regulon member .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Intriguingly , association of AraC with the site in dcp , as measured by ChIP/qPCR , is the highest of all AraC-bound regions in the E. coli genome ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>translation start site of araT is likely to be incorrectly annotated , and the downstream putative AraC site is likely to be located upstream of position 40 with respect to the araTU transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of ara operons by a truncated AraC protein does not require inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1943993" target="_blank">1943993</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC protein was puri ® ed to homogeneity by Jeff Withey ( Schleif & Favreau , 1982 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
<li>One operon , araFGH , codes for the well-studied AraC protein and by cyclic AMP ( cAMPt ) receptor protein ( CRP ) ( Englesberg et al. , 1965 ; Greenblatt & Schleif , 1971 ; Wilcox et al. , 1974 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in Rob the 100-residue domain homologous to SoxS and MarA is located at the N terminus of the protein ; the C-terminal 175-residue segment of Rob is not related to XylS-AraC family members ( 40 ) ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7896685" target="_blank">7896685</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both MarA and SoxS belong to the XylS/AraC family of transcription regulators ( 6 ) , and yet another member of this family , RobA , also increases acrAB expression ( 37 , 41 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107134" target="_blank">12107134</a>]<br></li>
<li>Its expression is regulated by three XylS/AraC family regulators , MarA , SoxS and Rob .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12791142" target="_blank">12791142</a>]<br></li>
<li>Eventually , the mutation was revealed by sequencing the yqhC gene ( asterisk ) , a member of the AraC transcriptional activator family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20543070" target="_blank">20543070</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose inhibits xylose gene expression through AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>We constructed a strain in which the yidC gene was under the transcriptional control of the AraC protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940994" target="_blank">12940994</a>]<br></li>
<li>The yhiX gene , whose expression was increased over 13-fold in the H-NS-defective strain ( Table 1 ) , encodes a protein similar to the AraC family of regulatory proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11298273" target="_blank">11298273</a>]<br></li>
<li>All three genes are divergently transcribed from ykgD ( Fig. 1A ) , encoding an uncharacterized AraC family transcriptional activator ( 43 ) whose expression was also significantly up-regulated after HOCl treatment .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24078635" target="_blank">24078635</a>]<br></li>
<li>pTolAIII derivative expression was regulated by the AraC ( TolAIII1 and TolAIII2 ) or LacI ( TolAIII3 ) repressor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11851406" target="_blank">11851406</a>]<br></li>
<li>From our study , we can conclude that , though the ligandfree forms of both E. coli AraC and MelR proteins strongly repress expression from their own promoters , different mechanisms are used for ligand-dependent switching to a state that can activate transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of oxyR in MV243-derived isolates was repressed by AraC encoded by the chromosome and LacI q encoded by pMV110 , and was induced with the addition of 1 mM IPTG and 0.05 % or 0.1 % arabinose for protein production or in vivo repression respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692164" target="_blank">10692164</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here we show , using both in vivo and in vitro experiments , that the ara0 , site is not normally occupied by AraC protein under repressing conditions , but that if AraC protein is overproduced and the ara0 , site is absent , ara0 , is then occupied and repression of pBAD can be observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>S3 in the supplemental material ) , suggesting that AraC directly represses transcription of ytfQ , albeit weakly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>S4 in the supplemental material ) , suggesting that AraC and intracellular arabinose levels are unaffected by the absence of these genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The observation that the melAB promoter is positively rather than negatively controlled ( Webster et al. , 1987 ) strongly suggested that meiR encodes a transcription activator , and this was corroborated by the discovery of sequence similarities between MelR and the well-characterized arabinose operon activator , AraC ( Henikoff et al. , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The rhaSR operon encodes the two L-rhamnose-speciﬁc activators , RhaS and RhaR ( 9 , 34 , 35 ) , which are both members of the AraC family of transcription activators ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11073923" target="_blank">11073923</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is not known whether AraC is bound to araOl in vivo in the absence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , ydeNM is a novel AraC-regulated operon that is directly repressed by AraC in an arabinose-dependent manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We identiﬁed two E. coli transcripts that are directly repressed by AraC : ytfQ and ydeNM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that ydeN and ydeM are transcribed as a two-gene operon that is repressed by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIG 3 Repression of ydeN by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , transcription of the araC gene is repressed by two AraC molecules that bind to two DNA sites ( O2 and I1 ) that ﬂank the araC promoter and are separated by 210 bp ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION At the E. coli arabinose operon regulatory region , transcription is repressed by the binding of two AraC molecules at two targets that are in the same orientation and separated by 210 bp , and a repression loop forms ( 4,5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC was ﬁrst identiﬁed in 1959 by virtue of the requirement of araC for the metabolism of L-arabinose ( 2 ) and is the ﬁrst-described positive regulator of transcription ( 3 , 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC has previously been shown to repress its own transcription by binding to a region overlapping the araC promoter elements ( 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , some operons require other factors for CRP to activate transcription , e.g. AraC at the araBAD promoter ( 25 ) , which are missing in the ROMA system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15520470" target="_blank">15520470</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of transcription of the araBAD and araFGH operons depends upon promoter occupancy by cyclic AMP receptor protein ( CRP ) ' and AraC protein ( 6 , 8 , 11 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this paper , we present a study of similar complex repression by a transcription factor that is related to AraC , the E. coli K-12 MelR protein , which represses transcription of its own gene , melR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose converts AraC from a repressor to an activator , and transcription of the three operons is rapidly and strongly induced ( 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10094697" target="_blank">10094697</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-independent repression of ytfQ transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-dependent repression of ydeNM transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>This paper concerns the inducing and repressing activities of AraC on the two promoters located in the regulatory region between the araC and araBAD genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3041410" target="_blank">3041410</a>]<br></li>
<li>This loop helps prevent AraC protein from entering its inducing state and helps hold the uninduced , or basal level , of expression of the araBAD genes at a low level .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternative loop formation also plays a role in the regulation of araBAD and araC expression by the AraC regulatory protein ( 9 , 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2211510" target="_blank">2211510</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC can act as both the activator and the repressor of the L-arab-inose BAD operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8087856" target="_blank">8087856</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the cya mutant strain , CRP would not be bound to its site , and AraC would be the only activator of araBAD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the second point , there is also an example that AraC positively and negatively regulates the araBAD operon , the mechanism of which might be similar to some extent to that of the GntII regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14593252" target="_blank">14593252</a>]<br></li>
<li>When the inducer is absent , araBAD and araC are repressed by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon addition of the inducer , AraC becomes an activator of the araBAD operon while continuing to repress the araC gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although it is evident that transcription of the xyl promoters is activated by D-xylose , we can not rule out the possibility of a transcriptional repression in the absence of an inducer , as in the case of the araBAD operon that is negatively regulated by AraC and DNA looping .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9371449" target="_blank">9371449</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro activation of the transcription of araBAD operon by AraC activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>The most intensely examined operon is araBAD , where AraC is required for repression and activation of BAD transcription ( reviewed by Schleif , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>The conformational change in AraC induced by the binding of L-arabinose ( 28 ) is necessary for its cooperative binding to araI and araI2 , which produces araBAD activation ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=3279415" target="_blank">3279415</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC protein stimulates expression of the araBAD operon and represses its own synthesis by binding at two different sites ( Lee et al. , 1981 ) , while the cI protein represses cro expression and simultaneously activates its own synthesis by binding at a single site , OR1 ( Ptashne et al. , 1976 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=6350602" target="_blank">6350602</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC protein is necessary for both positive and negative regulation of the araC-BAD operon , and alternate loops between AraC binding sites have been demonstrated under repressed and activated conditions ( Hamilt , on & Lee , 1988 ; Huo et al. , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848637" target="_blank">1848637</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION The araI site , located immediately upstream of the RNA polymerase binding site in the araBAD operon , is complexed with AraC protein both in the presence and absence of the inducer arabinose ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>operon is repressed by AraC protein ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of the araBAD operon is repressed by the action of AraC protein in a looped DNA complex with a single molecule of AraC bound to an upstream site , araO2 , and to the inducer site , araI ( 33 , 40 , 43 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of the repressed basal level as well as the induced level of expression of the arabinose operon in Escherichia coli involves DNA looping mediated by the AraC protein , AraC proteins bound to two distinct DNA sites and bound to each other to form a DNA loop ( 1-4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2643114" target="_blank">2643114</a>]<br></li>
<li>The araBAD promoter in Escherichia coli is regulated by two transcription factors , AraC and catabolite gene activator protein ( CAP ) ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription initiation at the promoter of the Escherichia coli araBAD operon is regulated both positively and negatively by the AraC protein ( 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2962192" target="_blank">2962192</a>]<br></li>
<li>Introduction The L-arabinose operon of Escherichia coli is both positively and negatively regulated by AraC protein ( for a review , see Schleif , 1987 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1560456" target="_blank">1560456</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC protein activates and represses the araBAD genes , depending upon the presence of the inducer and cAMP/CAP which change the occupancy of the different sites ( Reeder and Schleif , 1993 and references therein ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7545108" target="_blank">7545108</a>]<br></li>
<li>The RhaS protein , one of the AraC family members , activates expression of the and operons ( 10 , E. coli rhaBAD rhaT 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>The affinity of araO2 for AraC protein is insufficient for it to be occupied by AraC protein on its own .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2643114" target="_blank">2643114</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , we did not detect AraC association upstream of ydeN ( Fig. 1A ) , nor did we detect any signiﬁcant difference in expression of ydeN or ydeM between wild-type and araC mutant cells in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data presented here are not consistent with the repression of the araF promoter by AraC in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Discussion How does AraC repress the BAD operon in the absence of L-arabinose and how does it activate the BAD operon in the presence of L-arabinose ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8980677" target="_blank">8980677</a>]<br></li>
<li>Maximal expression of the arabinose transport genes , araE and araFGH , is also dependent upon both AraC protein-arabinose and CRP-cAMP ( Kolodrubetz & Schleif , 1981b , c ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2231717" target="_blank">2231717</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been proposed that araFGH and araEare also negatively regulated by AraC protein in the absence of arabinose ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been suggested that araFGH is also repressed by AraC protein in the absence of arabinose ( 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1400237" target="_blank">1400237</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC protein represses expression of the araBAD and araC promoters ( called ParaBAD and ParaC , respectively ) ( 62 , 99 , 114 , 117 , 144 -- 146 , 156 , 157 , 165 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result suggests that wild type AraC protein actively represses araFGH expression in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>In E. solution both in the presence and absence coli , the AraC protein controls expression of of arabinose ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9103202" target="_blank">9103202</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of arabinose , AraC protein activates the expression of the araBAD , araFGH , and araE promoters ( 6-10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>Model of AraC induction by L-arabinose at the araBAD promoter and relevant sites at the divergent araC promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the MerR protein represses merT when it is unliganded and activates transcription of merT when mercury is bound ( 109 ) , and similar effects of arabinose binding are observed in the regulation of araBAD by AraC ( 88 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7968922" target="_blank">7968922</a>]<br></li>
<li>Key words : peptidyl arm ; allosteric ; arabinose ; sedimentation ; self-association INTRODUCTION AraC protein , a regulator of the L-arabinose operon in Escherichia coli , represses transcription of the adjacent araBAD genes in the absence of arabinose and activates their transcription in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17173282" target="_blank">17173282</a>]<br></li>
<li>When bound with arabinose , AraC activates the transcription of the araBAD , araE , and araFGH operons and represses transcription from the araC operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20023096" target="_blank">20023096</a>]<br></li>
<li>E. coli AraC activates transcription of the araBAD , araFGH , araE , and araJ transcripts in the presence of its inducer , L-arabinose ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC positively regulates transcription of the four other operons in the presence of arabinose and represses transcription in its absence ( 34 , 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10094697" target="_blank">10094697</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC protein negatively regulates the transcription of the araBAD operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1447222" target="_blank">1447222</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of L-arabinose , AraC represses transcription of araBAD ( 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2521619" target="_blank">2521619</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC represses transcription of araBAD and araC by forming a repression loop mediated by dimerization of distally bound AraC monomers ( 5 , 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>ygeA and polB are positively regulated by AraC and arabinose due to partial read-through of Rho-independent terminators ( Fig. 2 , 4 , and 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>This promoter is under the cmítrol of the AraC repressor and expression is induced with arabinose ( 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9125116" target="_blank">9125116</a>]<br></li>
<li>This variant of the wild-type pBAD promoter possesses a normal basal level and can be activated by CAP to a high level even when AraC is not induced by arabinose ( reference 32 and data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9440505" target="_blank">9440505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of the araJ gene encoding arabinose efﬂux transporter is under the control of an arabinose-inducible AraC and two molecules of CRP , one ( 90.5 ) upstream of AraC and another ( +44.5 ) downstream of the promoter ( Hendrickson et al. , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24814025" target="_blank">24814025</a>]<br></li>
<li>Only one indirect target gene , isrB , is upregulated 4-fold by both AraC and arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We did not detect any signiﬁcant differences in RNAP association , suggesting that under these growth conditions , AraC does not regulate expression of a transcript that initiates within dcp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We did not detect any signiﬁcant change in expression of sseD or the surrounding genes , suggesting that , like E. coli dcp , this gene contains an AraC binding site that is not associated with regulation of transcription under the conditions tested .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We did not detect signiﬁcant regulation of ytfQ or ppa by AraC or arabinose in the transcription proﬁling experiment ; however , ytfQ encodes a transporter that binds arabinose and galactose ( 39 ) , consistent with ytfQ being a regulatory target of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We did not detect regulation of polB by AraC in S. enterica .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ChIP-chip analysis identiﬁed binding of AraC upstream of ytfQ and ppa ( divergently transcribed genes ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Three of these genes , ytfQ , araT , and araU , have not previously been described as AraC targets .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>This mechanism may not bc possible in t , he ara02-independent act ' ivat , ion of pBAD by ( IRP , considering that AraC ' is bound bet ' wcen C'RI ' and R'NA polymerasc when t ' hr operon is both repressed and induced ( Martin rt ~ 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1848302" target="_blank">1848302</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consequently , we should be able to derive a quantitative description that predicts , under a wide variety of conditions , the fraction of operon copies in which AraC loops between I1 and O2 to repress pBAD and the fraction in which AraC binds to I1-I2 to induce pBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9600836" target="_blank">9600836</a>]<br></li>
